{"title_page": "Anti-Defamation League", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name         = Anti-Defamation League\n|image        = ADL logo (2018).svg\n|size         = 200px\n|motto        = Fighting Hate for Good\n|formation    = {{Start date and age|1913|09}} (as Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith)\n|founder      = [[Sigmund Livingston]]\n|headquarters = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|type         = [[Civil rights]] law\n|leader_title = Director\n|leader_name  = [[Jonathan Greenblatt]]\n|key_people   = Sigmund Livingston (Founder)<br />Robert G. Sugarman (Chairman)\n|website      = [http://www.adl.org/ www.adl.org/]\n}}\n{{Antisemitism}}\nThe '''Anti-Defamation League''' ('''ADL'''; formerly known as the '''Anti-Defamation League of [[B'nai B'rith]]''') is an international [[Jews|Jewish]] [[non-governmental organization]] based in the [[United States]]. It was founded in late September 1913 by the Independent Order of [[B'nai B'rith]], a [[Jews|Jewish]] [[service organization]]. ADL subsequently split from B'nai B'rith and continued as an independent U.S. Section 501(c)(3) nonprofit. In its 2017 annual information Form 990, ADL reported total revenues of just over $70 million, from contributions and grants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdf.guidestar.org/PDF_Images/2017/131/818/2017-131818723-1035a764-9.pdf|title=ANTI-DEFAMATION LEAGUE FORM 990|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nADL states that its mission is a dual one: \"To stop the defamation of the Jewish people, and to secure justice and fair treatment to all\" via the development of \"new programs, policies and skills to expose and combat whatever holds us back.\"<ref name=\"ADLCharter\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-mission|title=Our Mission|website=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> Opposing [[Antisemitism]] and extremism, ADL describes its \"ultimate goal\" as \"a world in which no group or individual suffers from bias, discrimination or hate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are|title=Who We Are|website=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe headquarters of ADL are located in [[New York City]]. [[Abraham Foxman]] was the national director from 1987 for more than a quarter century. In November 2014, it was announced that [[Jonathan Greenblatt]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/leadership/staff/jonathan-greenblatt|title=Jonathan Greenblatt, CEO and National Director|last=Anti-Defamation League|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> a serial social entrepreneur, former Silicon Valley tech executive and former Obama Administration official who had not operated within the Jewish communal organization world prior to his hiring, would succeed Foxman as national director in July 2015.<ref>[http://www.jta.org/2014/11/06/news-opinion/united-states/white-house-aide-to-succeed-abe-foxman-as-adl-chief-1 \"White House aide Jonathan Greenblatt to succeed Abe Foxman as ADL chief\"], ''[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]'', November 6, 2014.</ref> The national chair of the governing board of directors is Esta Gordon Epstein; she is the second woman to hold the organization's top volunteer leadership post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newengland.adl.org/news/longtime-adl-boston-leader-esta-epstein-named-chair-of-organizations-national-board/|title=LONGTIME ADL BOSTON LEADER ESTA GORDON EPSTEIN NAMED CHAIR OF ORGANIZATION'S NATIONAL BOARD|last=|first=|date=November 8, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>[http://www.adl.org/about-adl/adl-leadership.html Barry Curtiss-Lusher, National Chair] ADL.org, ''accessed November 9, 2014.''</ref> ADL has 25 regional offices in the United States<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/anti-semitism/anti-semitism-in-the-us|title=Anti-Semitism in the US|work=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019|quote=Through our network of 25 regional offices}}</ref> including a Government Relations Office in Washington DC, and is also active overseas, with an office in Israel and staff in Europe.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/anti-semitism/anti-semitism-globally|title=Anti-Semitism Globally|work=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nADL has been criticized both from the right<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/12/anti-defamation-league-trump-232049|title=ADL combats criticism of being too tough on Trump|last=|first=|date=January 1, 2016|website=Politico.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> and left of the U.S. political spectrum, including within the American Jewish community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/opinion/.premium-from-left-and-right-why-is-a-league-of-haters-descending-on-the-adl-1.6053744|title=Opinion From Left and Right, Why Is a League of Haters Descending on the ADL?|newspaper=Haaretz|date=May 3, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020|last1=Cohen|first1=Debra Nussbaum}}</ref> Some of the criticism from the left, or at least from the far left, is based on ADL's support for [[Israel]] as a Jewish homeland and the organization's vocal opposition to attempts to equate [[Zionism]], the national movement for a state for the Jewish people, with racism. Indeed, this stance has led some on the farther reaches of the American left (including some Jewish groups, such as [[Jewish Voice for Peace]]) to claim that so long as ADL continues to support Israel as a Jewish homeland, it cannot credibly call itself a civil rights organization, regardless of any other civil rights positions it takes domestically or internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.losangelesblade.com/2019/01/31/creating-change-2019-creates-controversy-again/|title=Creating Change 2019 creates controversy, again|last=|first=|date=January 31, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://droptheadl.wordpress.com/why-droptheadl/|title=#DropTheADL: Communities say NO to the Anti-Defamation League in our schools, coalitions, and movements|last=|first=|date=May 30, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther ADL positions and actions, past and present, that have generated criticism from the left include domestic spying allegations, its former stance on the [[Armenian Genocide]],<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|first1=Rupen|last1=Janbazian|accessdate=2019-09-25|title=ADL's Official Recognition of Armenian Genocide Ends Years-Long Controversy|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2016/05/16/adl-armenian-genocide-2016/|date=16 May 2016|website=The Armenian Weekly}}</ref> since repudiated and apologized for,<ref name=\":0\" /> and what frequently is alleged by the left to be ADL's conflation of opposition to Israel with [[antisemitism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/how-a-jewish-civil-rights-group-became-a-villain-on-the-far-left/|title=How a Jewish civil rights group became a villain on the far-left|last=Sales|first=Ben|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Shira|last1=Hanau|accessdate=2019-09-25|title=Can ADL Be A Moral Voice For Millennials?|url=https://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/can-adl-be-a-moral-voice-for-millennials/|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com}}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, rightwing groups and pundits, including very conservative Jewish groups, have attacked ADL, labeling it an arm of the Democratic party (presumably in part because its CEO, [[Jonathan Greenblatt]], was in the Obama administration)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/amari-sohrab/the-adl-smears-mike-pompeo/|title=The ADL Smears Mike Pompeo|last=Ahmari|first=Sohrab|date=April 19, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jns.org/opinion/whatever-happened-to-the-adl/|title=Whatever happened to the ADL?: The attack on Kavanaugh's nomination to the Supreme Court is the latest instance of how Jonathan Greenblatt has turned the venerable anti-Semitism watchdog into a partisan outfit.|last=Tobin|first=Jonathan|date=July 13, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> and decrying its civil rights agenda, which supports immigrants and refugees, trans rights and other [[LGBT|LGBTQ]] rights, and advocates against establishment of religion, as well as against [[Islamophobia|Islamaphobia]]. In mid 2018 ADL publicly raised concerns over President Donald Trump's nomination of then-DC Circuit Court of Appeals judge [[Brett Kavanaugh]] as an Associate Justice of the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-response-to-the-presidents-nomination-of-judge-brett-kavanaugh-to-serve-as|title=ADL Response to the President's Nomination of Judge Brett Kavanaugh to Serve as an Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court|last=|first=|date=July 9, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsmax.com/newsfront/brett-kavanaugh-scotus-adl-senate/2018/07/12/id/871445/|title=ADL 'Concerned' About Kavanaugh Nomination|last=Beamon|first=Todd|date=July 12, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/jewish-groups-slam-trump-s-supreme-court-nominee-kavanaugh-1.6264823|title=Jewish Groups Slam Trump's Supreme Court Nominee Kavanaugh|last=|first=|date=July 10, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>Despite the fact that ADL had for many years submitted questions to the Senate Judiciary Committee for Supreme Court and other key government nominations,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/media-watch/letter-to-the-wall-street-journal-regarding-criticism-of-adls-stance-on-judge|title=Letter to the Wall Street Journal Regarding Criticism of ADL's Stance on Judge Kavanaugh|last=Sugarman|first=Robert G.|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> the organization and CEO Jonathan Greenblatt were harshly criticized by many on the right for raising concerns in this instance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freebeacon.com/issues/anti-defamation-league-criticized-entering-partisan-kavanaugh-confirmation-fight/|title=Anti-Defamation League Criticized for Entering Partisan Kavanaugh Confirmation Fight|last=|first=|date=July 26, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, in another move that enraged many on the right, the ADL called for the resignation or firing of Trump administration official [[Stephen Miller (political advisor)|Stephen Miller]], the architect of the Administration's immigration policy, on the basis of his association with white supremacists.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/jewish-groups-stephen-miller-resign-white-nationalist_n_5dd69935e4b0e29d72800575?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly91cy5zZWFyY2gueWFob28uY29tLw&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAG5GoJ0dtOkPudr5tkzXMWY-wRmtd1nHDOfZ1c7WOW3gYQKtSQgDjZaIXDUnko0UMrEJVEYUXG3jMWrrsrV52jBKycFPCh7lje-saS6lbR17o5_4ikE4B7PIIACorUKfLxJXapH0BueU1WTMTER8dUqZKRH2Ep2TZ2Y83nmA0kDE|title=Jewish Groups Demand Stephen Miller Resign From White House|last=Mathias|first=Christopher|date=November 21, 2019|website=HuffPost|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Jewish-groups-again-call-for-Stephen-Miller-to-quit-614202|title=Jewish groups again call for Stephen Miller to quit|last=Kampeas|first=Ron|date=January 15, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Origin ==\nFounded in late September 1913 by [[B'nai B'rith]], with [[Sigmund Livingston]] as its first leader, the ADL's charter states, {{quote|The immediate object of the League is to stop, by appeals to reason and conscience and, if necessary, by appeals to law, the defamation of the Jewish people. Its ultimate purpose is to secure justice and fair treatment to all citizens alike and to put an end forever to unjust and unfair discrimination against and ridicule of any sect or body of citizens.<ref name=ADLCharter />}}\nThe Anti-Defamation League was founded by B'nai B'rith as a response to attacks on Jews; the recent conviction of [[Leo Frank]] was mentioned by [[Adolf Kraus]] when he announced the creation of ADL.<ref>{{cite book|last=Moore|first=Deborah Dash|title=B'nai B'rith and the Challenge of Ethnic Leadership|year=1981|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-87395-480-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/bnaibrithch00moor/page/108 108]|url=https://archive.org/details/bnaibrithch00moor/page/108}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Jews in American Politics: Essays|year=2001|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-7425-0181-2|page=105|author=Jerome A. Chanes|editor1=Louis S |editor2=y Maisel |editor3=Ira N. Forman |editor4=Donald Altschiller |editor5=Charles Walker Bassett |chapter=Who Does What?}}</ref>\n\n== Goals ==\n[[File:Jonathan Greenblatt by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|Jonathan Greenblatt, National Director and CEO of the Anti-Defamation League since 2015]]\nThe stated purpose of the ADL is to fight: {{quote|anti-Semitism and all forms of bigotry (in the United States) and abroad, combat international terrorism, probe the roots of hatred, advocate before the United States Congress, come to the aid of victims of bigotry, develop educational programs, and serve as a public resource for government, media, law enforcement, and the public, all towards the goal of countering and reducing hatred.}} Historically, ADL has opposed groups and individuals it considered to be anti-Semitic and/or racist, including: [[Nazism|Nazis]], the [[Ku Klux Klan]], [[Henry Ford]], Father [[Charles Coughlin]] (leader of the [[Christian Front (United States)|Christian Front]]), Nation of Islam leader [[Louis Farrakhan]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Antisemitism/ADL-pans-congressman-who-wont-condemn-Farrakhan-for-lacking-courage-544221|title=ADL pans congressman who won\u2019t condemn Farrakhan for lacking 'courage'|last=|first=|date=March 5, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> the [[Christian Identity]] movement, the [[German-American Bund]], [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazis]], the [[Militia (United States)|American militia]] movement and [[white power skinhead]]s (although ADL acknowledges that there are also non-racist [[skinhead]]s).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/racist_skinheads/ |title=Racist Skinhead Project |publisher=ADL}}</ref><ref>Salberg, Melvin. [https://www.nytimes.com/1994/04/29/opinion/l-adl-acknowledges-nonracist-skinheads-932108.html Letter to the editor (\"A.D.L. Acknowledges Nonracist Skinheads\")]. ''The New York Times''. April 29, 1994.</ref> ADL publishes reports on a variety of countries, regarding alleged incidents of anti-Jewish attacks and propaganda.  Along with the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC), ADL's Center on Extremism (COE) is generally viewed as the most authoritative non-governmental experts on domestic extremists in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/20/us/hate-groups-rise.html|title=Over 1,000 Hate Groups Are Now Active in United States, Civil Rights Group Says|last=Stack|first=Liam|date=February 20, 2019|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nADL maintains that some forms of [[anti-Zionism]] and [[criticism of Israel]] cross the line into anti-Semitism. The Anti-Defamation League states:\n{{quote|Criticism of particular Israeli actions or policies in and of itself does not constitute anti-Semitism. Certainly the sovereign State of Israel can be legitimately criticized just like any other country in the world. However, it is undeniable that there are those whose criticism of Israel or of \"Zionism\" is used to mask anti-Semitism.<ref>{{cite web|title=Response To Common Inaccuracy: Israel Critics are Anti-Semites|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/fact-sheets/response-to-common-inaccuracy-israel-critics-are-anti-semites|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 2010, ADL published a list of the \"ten leading organizations responsible for maligning Israel in the US\", which has included [[ANSWER]], the [[International Solidarity Movement]], and [[Jewish Voice for Peace]] for its call for [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|BDS]].<ref>Benhorin, Yitzhak. \"[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3969798,00.html Jewish group makes ADL blacklist].\" ynet news. October 15, 2010.</ref>  It has not published such a list since.\n\n=== Fighting antisemitism ===\nIn the second decade of the 21st century ADL and Jews, as well as non-Jews, throughout the United States were generally shocked at the global resurgence of antisemitism,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pope-antisemitism-idUSKBN1ZJ1LT|title=Pope condemns 'barbaric resurgence' of anti-Semitism|last=|first=|newspaper=Reuters|date=January 20, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> which was manifested in the rise of white supremacist extremist activity both online and off.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/17/695593556/-antisemitism-here-and-now-author-discusses-resurgence-of-public-anti-semitism|title='Antisemitism: Here And Now' Author Discusses Resurgence Of Public Anti-Semitism|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/anti-semitic-assaults-u-s-more-doubled-2018-adl-reports-n1000246|title=Anti-Semitic assaults in the U.S. more than doubled in 2018, ADL reports|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> A foundational theme of white supremacists was antisemitism, which accompanied or underlay the anti-Muslim, xenophobic, racist, homophobic and other bigotry of these individuals and groups.<ref name=\":3\" /> Social media in particular, amplified hatred and provided what ADL officials characterized as a virtual \"24/7 neo-Nazi rally.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishwebsite.com/featured/adl-urges-congress-to-help-social-media-giants-address-anti-semitism/50933/|title=ADL urges Congress to help social media giants address anti-Semitism|last=|first=|date=January 16, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The number of [[hate crime]]s and extremist murders shook the ADL, leading it to reformulate its strategy so it could devote more of its resources to fighting antisemitism and [[extremism]]: the [[Unite the Right rally|2017 white supremacist rally]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], during which extremists chanted \"Jews will not replace us\" and which led to the murder of [[Charlottesville car attack|Heather Heyer]]; [[Dylann Roof|Dylan Roof]]'s [[Charleston church shooting|2015 massacre of African Americans]] at a prayer group in [[Charleston, South Carolina]]; the murder of 11 Jews at Sabbath services in the 2018 [[Pittsburgh synagogue shooting]]; the 2019 [[Poway synagogue shooting]] in California; the 2019 [[Christchurch mosque shooting]]<nowiki/>s in New Zealand; the 2019 Monsey, NY [[Monsey Hanukkah stabbing|Hanukkah stabbing]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/30/opinion/monsey-new-york-attack.html|title=The Right Response to the Anti-Semitic Attack in Monsey, N.Y.|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 30, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020|last1=Lowey|first1=Nita|last2=Harris|first2=David}}</ref> the series of antisemitic hate crimes in Brooklyn, NY in December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/12/27/jewish-mom-son-assaulted-in-latest-anti-semitic-attack-in-brooklyn/|title=Four Jewish women targeted in latest anti-Semitic attacks in Brooklyn|last=|first=|date=December 27, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL has financially supported litigation against the organizers of the Charlottesville rally,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-announces-support-for-ifas-lawsuit-against-neo-nazis-white-supremacists-and|title=ADL Announces Support for IFA's Lawsuit Against Neo-Nazis, White Supremacists, and Hate Groups Responsible for Charlottesville Violence|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> lobbied for an array of federal and state laws and policies which are designed to track, expose, and combat extremism, and developed and marketed education programs about the subject.<ref name=\":4\" />  ADL also works in close collaboration with Law Enforcement in response to hate crimes.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/anti-semitism/anti-semitism-in-the-us|title=Anti-Semitism in the US|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, after a year's work, ADL published ''Antisemitism Uncovered: A Guide to Old Myths in a New Era.''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://antisemitism.adl.org/?_ga=2.171810404.555282254.1584044588-1012598960.1553545971|title=Antisemitism Uncovered: A Guide to Old Myths in a New Era|last=Anti-Defamation League|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The Guide is intended to be \"a comprehensive resource with historical context, fact-based descriptions of prevalent antisemitic myths, contemporary examples and calls-to-action for addressing this hate.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> It is organized around seven \"myths\" or antisemitic tropes, and composed of modules.<ref name=\":1\" /> This Guide also represented ADL's shift from using the spelling \"anti-Semitism\" to \"antisemitism.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://antisemitism.adl.org/?_ga=2.171810404.555282254.1584044588-1012598960.1553545971|title=Antisemitism Uncovered: Notes from the CEO, Footnote 8|last=|first=|date=|website=ADL|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/culture/166092/should-anti-semitism-be-hyphenated/|title=Should anti-semitism be hyphenated|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] also saw the launch of Jew hatred and at least two types of conspiracy theories that were resuscitated and revised so they could encompass the virus crisis,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/listen-tablets-yair-rosenberg-talks-anti-semitism-during-coronavirus-crisis/|title=Listen: Tablet's Yair Rosenberg talks anti-Semitism during coronavirus crisis|last=Rosenberg|first=Yair|date=March 27, 2020|website=The Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> an analysis with which ADL agreed and also exposed. \"'There are people out there in the conspiracy theorist swamp who are talking about this being some kind of Mossad thing, or Israel-operative thing,' Rosenberg said. And there's the other type of theorist 'who just celebrates when Jews die from it, under the cover that anti-Zionism makes it okay to celebrate when random people die.' Many of these people, he said, tweeted horrific things after Israel's first victim, Holocaust survivor Aryeh Stern, passed away.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=@JGreenblattADL|title=Tweet re@yair_rosenberg on #antisemitism and #coronavirusMarch|last=|first=|date=March 27, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Tracking extremists ===\nDuring the 1930s, ADL, along with the American Jewish Committee, coordinated American Jewish groups across the country in monitoring the activities of the German-American Bund and its pro-Nazis, nativist allies in the United States. In many instances, these community-based defense organizations paid informants to infiltrate these groups and report on what they discovered. The longest-lived and most effective of these American Jewish resistance organizations was the Los Angeles Jewish Community Committee (LAJCC), which was backed financially by the Jewish leaders of the motion picture industry. The day-to-day operations of the LAJCC were supervised by a Jewish attorney, [[Leon L. Lewis]]. Lewis was uniquely qualified to combat the rise of Nazism in Los Angeles, having served as the first national secretary of the Anti-Defamation League in Chicago from 1925\u20131931. From 1934\u20131941, the LAJCC maintained its undercover surveillance of the German-American Bund, the Silver Shirts and dozens of other pro-Nazi, nativist groups that operated in Los Angeles. Partnering with the American Legion in Los Angeles, the LAJCC channeled eyewitness accounts of sedition onto federal authorities. Working with the ADL, Leon Lewis and the LAJCC played a strategic role in counseling the McCormack-Dickstein Committee investigation of Nazi propaganda activities in the United States (1934) and the Dies Committee investigation of \"un-American activities\" (1938-1940). In their final reports to Congress, both Committees found that the sudden rise in political antisemitism in the United States during the decade was due, in part, to the German government's support of these domestic groups.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rosenzweig|first=Laura|url=https://nyupress.org/books/9781479855179/|title=Hollywood's Spies: The Undercover Surveillance of Nazis in Los Angeles|date=2017|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=9781479855179|location=New York|page=|author-link=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ross|first=Steven|url=https://www.bloomsbury.com/us/hitler-in-los-angeles-9781620405642/|title=Hitler in Los Angeles: How Jews Foiled Nazi Plots Against Hollywood and America|date=2017|publisher=Bloomsbury|isbn=9781620405642|location=New York|page=|author-link=}}</ref>\n\nSince the 1970s, ADL has partnered with the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) field offices, sharing information learned from monitoring of extremist groups.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=5SOAAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA167 \"Confronting Right Wing Extremism and Terrorism in the USA\"], George Michael. Routledge, Sep 2, 2003. p. 167. Retrieved 27 feb 2017</ref>  In April 2020, ADL joined with [[George Washington University's Program on Extremism]] to release a joint report on white supremacist terrorism, which supported additional government actions to combat the surging threat; the release of the report was timed to occur the same day that the U.S. government, for the first time, designated a white supremacist group and individuals associated with it a [[Special Designated Global Terrorist|Specially Designated Global Terrorist]] ([[Specially Designated Global Terrorist|SDGT]]) organization - akin to the [[United States Department of State list of Foreign Terrorist Organizations|Foreign Terrorist Organization]] (FTO) designation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.homelandsecuritynewswire.com/dr20200407-new-report-outlines-tactics-of-modern-whitesupremacist-terrorism|title=New Report Outlines Tactics of Modern White-Supremacist Terrorism|last=|first=|date=April 7, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hstoday.us/subject-matter-areas/counterterrorism/report-u-s-has-struggled-to-adapt-to-changing-domestic-terrorism-landscape/|title=Report: U.S. Has Struggled to Adapt to Changing Domestic Terrorism Landscape|last=|first=|date=April 7, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nADL keeps track of the activities of extremist groups and movements, primarily through its Center on Extremism.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/sites/default/files/documents/assets/pdf/combating-hate/ADL_CR_Bigots_on_Bikes_online.pdf|title=Bigots on Bikes: The Growing Links between White Supremacists and Biker Gangs|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-on-extremism|title=Center on Extremism|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> According to ADL Director Abe Foxman: \"Our mission is to monitor and expose those who are anti-Jewish, racist, anti-democratic, and violence-prone, and we monitor them primarily by reading publications and attending public meetings \u2026. Because extremist organizations are highly secretive, sometimes ADL can learn of their activities only by using undercover sources \u2026 [who] function in a manner directly analogous to investigative journalists. Some have performed great service to the American people\u2014for example, by uncovering the existence of right-wing extremist paramilitary training camps\u2014with no recognition and at considerable personal risk.\"<ref>\"A League of His Own\", letter to the editor, ''The Village Voice'' 38:20 (May 18, 1993)</ref> A person apprehended in connection to the [[2002 white supremacist terror plot]] had drawn a cartoon of himself blowing up the Boston offices of ADL.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/16/national/16PLOT.html|title=Boston Couple Plotted Blasts to Incite Race War, Prosecutor Says|date=July 16, 2002|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nADL regularly releases reports on [[Anti-Semitism in the USA|US anti-Semitism]] and extremist activities on both the [[Far-left politics|far left]] and the [[Far-right politics|far right]]. As part of its Law Enforcement Agency Resource Network (L.E.A.R.N.), ADL has published information about the [[Militia Movement]]<ref name=\"militia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/militia-movement|title=The Militia Movement|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en}}</ref> in America and a guide for law enforcement officials titled ''Officer Safety and Extremists''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/sites/default/files/documents/assets/pdf/combating-hate/Officer-Safety-and-Extremists-An-Overview.pdf|title=Officer Safety and Extremists|publisher=ADL|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref> An archive of \"[[Mark Pitcavage#Militia Watchdog|The Militia Watchdog]]\" research on U.S. right-wing extremism (including groups not specifically cited as anti-Semitic) from 1995 to 2000 is also available on ADL website.<ref name=\"militia\" />\n\nIn the 1990s, some details of ADL's monitoring activities became public knowledge; the ADL had gathered information about some non-extremist groups which became a contentious issue. In 2013, J.M. Berger, a former nonresident fellow of the [[Brookings Institution]], wrote that media organizations should be more cautious when citing the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC) and ADL, arguing that they are \"not objective purveyors of data\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Berger|first1=J. M.|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2013/03/12/the-hate-list/|title=The Hate List|work=Foreign Policy}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, ADL announced that they would be developing profiles on 36 [[alt-right]] and [[alt-lite]] leaders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/adl-releases-whos-who-guide-of-alt-right-and-alt-lite-extremists/|title=ADL releases 'Who's Who' guide of alt-right and alt-lite extremists|work=The Times of Israel|access-date=2017-07-19|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/from-alt-right-to-alt-lite-naming-the-hate|title=From Alt Right to Alt Lite: Naming the Hate|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref>  In 2019 and 2020 ADL executives and staff testified multiple times in front of Congressional committees concerning the dangers of domestic extremists,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/policy/defense-national-security/how-to-stop-it-congress-asks-what-the-military-is-doing-about-white-nationalism-in-the-ranks|title='How to stop it': Congress asks what the military is doing about white nationalism in its ranks|last=|first=|date=February 12, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> noting that the large majority of extremist murders in the United States over the past decade had been committed by white supremacists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/i-testified-at-a-congressional-hearing-on-white-nationalism-heres-some-of-what-i-wish-we-had|title=I Testified at a Congressional Hearing on White Nationalism. Here's Some of What I Wish We Had Discussed.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/adl-tells-congress-to-curb-online-hate-speech-if-social-media-giants-wont/|title=ADL tells Congress to curb online hate speech if social media giants won't|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> In early 2020, as the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Coronavirus pandemic]] raged, ADL's Center on Extremism<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-on-extremism|title=Who We Are: Center on Extremism|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> began tracking and publishing reports of upsurges in extremist hate and violence targeting Asian-Americans, Chinese, Jews and immigrants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/coronavirus-crisis-elevates-antisemitic-racist-tropes|title=Coronavirus Elevates Antisemitic Racist Tropes|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2020/03/20/yang-anti-defamation-league-ceo-avoid-coronavirus-scapegoating-racism-column/2877976001/|title=Yang & Anti-Defamation League CEO: Avoid coronavirus racism and scapegoating|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Separation of church and state   ===\nOne of ADL's major focuses is [[Freedom of religion#Judaism|religious freedom]] for people of all faiths.<ref name=\"RelFree\">{{cite web|title=Primer on the First Amendment & Religious Freedom|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/the-first-amendment-and-religious-freedom|website=Anti-Defamation League|accessdate=11 May 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Religious Freedom|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/discrimination/religious-freedom|website=Anti-Defamation League|accessdate=11 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> In the context of public schools, ADL has taken the position that because [[creationism]] and [[intelligent design]] are religious beliefs, and the government is prohibited from endorsing the beliefs of any particular religion, they should not be taught in [[science]] classrooms: \"The U.S. Constitution guarantees the rights of Americans to believe the religious theories of creation (as well as other theories), but it does not permit them to be taught in public school science classes.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adl.org/issue_religious_freedom/create/creationism_QA.asp |title=Religion in the Science Class? Why Creationism and Intelligent Design Don't Belong |publisher=ADL |access-date=March 6, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020407123320/http://www.adl.org/issue_religious_freedom/create/creationism_QA.asp |archive-date=April 7, 2002 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Similarly, ADL supports the legal precedent that it is [[constitutionality|unconstitutional]] for the government to post the [[Ten Commandments]] in courthouses, schools, and other public places: \"True religious liberty means freedom from having the government impose the religion of the majority on all citizens.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adl.org/10comm/Prohibitions.asp |title=The Ten Commandments Controversy: A First Amendment Perspective \u2013 Prohibitions on Display of the Ten Commandments |publisher=ADL |access-date=March 7, 2006 |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20020920090047/http://www.adl.org/10comm/prohibitions.asp |archive-date=September 20, 2002 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ADL has also condemned the public school [[Bible]] curriculum published by the [[National Council on Bible Curriculum in Public Schools]], saying that it raises \"serious constitutional problems\" and \"advocates the acceptance of one faith tradition's interpretation of the Bible over another\".<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Says Bible Teaching Guide for Public Schools 'Unacceptable' |publisher=ADL |date=November 7, 2005 |url=http://www.jewsonfirst.org/05a/public024.html |access-date=July 11, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022212940/http://www.jewsonfirst.org/05a/public024.html |archive-date=October 22, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 ADL opposed [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|Proposition 8]] in California; Prop 8 was a successful ballot proposition for a state constitutional amendment opposing same sex marriage that was subsequently overturned by the federal courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2008_California_Proposition_8|title=2008 California Proposition 8|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> ADL submitted amicus briefs supporting same sex marriage in those cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://38.106.4.56/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentID=1228|title=BRIEF OF AMICI CURIAE ANTI-DEFAMATION LEAGUE ET AL. IN SUPPORT OF RESPONDENTS|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307154233/http://38.106.4.56/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentID=1228|archive-date=March 7, 2013|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> While basing its ongoing opposition to that and other anti-LGBTQ+ laws and campaigns primarily on equality and anti-discrimination legal rationales, ADL also consistently cites church/state separation arguments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/its-not-ok-for-businesses-to-discriminate-in-the-name-of-religion|title=It's Not OK for Businesses to Discriminate in the Name of Religion|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Thus, a frequent theme of ADL argument is that freedom of religion was meant to be a shield to protect religious freedom (particularly of minorities and vulnerable constituencies), and not a sword to attack the religious freedom of others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/ADL-slams-controversial-religious-freedom-laws-in-US-396007|title=ADL slams controversial 'religious freedom' laws in US|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nADL has also based its support for women's equality and reproductive choice on, among other legal arguments, the argument that the state should not adopt as law a particular religious belief,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/abortion-bans-undermine-equality-for-all|title=Abortion and Religious Freedom: The Right-Wing Assault on Religious Diversity in Reproductive Freedom|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> although the United States federal courts have not accepted this religious freedom and state/church separation line of argument.\n\n=== Holocaust awareness ===\nADL holds the view that it is important to remember [[the Holocaust]], in order to prevent such an event from reoccurring. Along with sponsoring events opposing [[Holocaust denial|Holocaust deniers]] and revisionists, ADL has been active in urging action to end modern-day [[ethnic cleansing]] and [[genocide]] in places such as [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]], [[Darfur]], and [[Sudan]].{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} ADL gives out its [[Courage to Care Award]] to honor rescuers of Jews during the Holocaust.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}} ADL has also sharply criticized Holocaust Denial as antisemitism and particularly singled out Facebook for its refusal to remove Holocaust denial content from its platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2020/01/26/auschwitz-liberation-ban-holocaust-denial-on-facebook-column/4555483002/|title=Facebook should ban Holocaust denial to mark 75th anniversary of Auschwitz liberation|last=Greenblatt|first=Jonathan|date=January 26, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nADL spoke out against an advertising campaign by [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals]] (PETA) beginning in 2003 that equated meat-eating with the Holocaust. A press release from ADL stated that, \"PETA's effort to seek 'approval' for their 'Holocaust on Your Plate' campaign is outrageous, offensive and takes chutzpah to new heights. Rather than deepen our revulsion against what the Nazis did to the Jews, the project will undermine the struggle to understand the Holocaust and find ways to make sure such catastrophes never happen again.\"<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Denounces Peta for its \"Holocaust On Your Plate\" Campaign; Calls Appeal for Jewish Community Support 'The Height Of Chutzpah' |publisher=ADL |date=February 24, 2003 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/HolNa_52/4235_52.htm}}</ref> In May 2005, PETA apologized for its campaign, with PETA President [[Ingrid Newkirk]] stating that causing pain \"was never our intention, and we are deeply sorry\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Rabbinate to phase out 'shackle and hoist' animal slaughter. More humane method to be adopted following claims of cruelty|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=February 19, 2008|last=Wagner|first=Matthew|quote=PETA has denied being motivated by anti-Semitism and even mentions on its Web site the humaneness of traditional Jewish slaughtering methods when done properly. However, PETA has a history of controversial campaigns. On May 5, 2005, PETA issued an apology for its 'Holocaust on Your Plate' exhibit, which traveled to more than 100 cities. The exhibit compared the treatment of farm animals to that of victims of the Nazi concentration camps. PETA President Ingrid Newkirk said she realized that the campaign had caused pain: 'This was never our intention, and we are deeply sorry.'}}</ref>\n\nADL's Education Department focuses on Holocaust and Genocide Education, primarily through its Echoes and Reflections Program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://echoesandreflections.org/|title=CONFIDENTLY TEACH ABOUT THE HOLOCAUST |website=Echoes & Reflections|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Echoes and Reflections is sponsored by ADL, [[Yad Vashem]], and the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|United States Holocaust Museum]]. In 2019\u201320, ADL's national lobbying group and the regional offices refocused efforts on federal and state funding of Holocaust and genocide education, in part as a result of the upsurge of antisemitism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/why-we-need-legislation-to-ensure-the-holocaust-is-taught-in-schools|title=Why We Need Legislation to Ensure the Holocaust is Taught in Schools|last=|first=|date=February 21, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Federal and State Hate Crimes Legislation ===\nADL was also one of the lead organizations campaigning for thirteen years, ultimately successfully, for the [[Matthew Shepard Act|Matthew Shepard and James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Prevention Act.]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.duke.edu/news/michael-lieberman-81/|title=Michael Lieberman '81|last=|first=|date=|website=Duke Law News Releases|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/attorney-general-loretta-e-lynch-hosts-63rd-annual-attorney-general-awards-honoring|title=Attorney General Loretta E. Lynch Hosts the 63rd Annual Attorney General Awards Honoring Department Employees and Others For Their Service|last=|first=|date=October 21, 2015|website=|page=|type=U.S. Department of Justice News Release|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>  The hold-up in passing that law focused on the inclusion of the term \"sexual orientation\" as one of the bases that a crime could be deemed a hate crime.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/year-blaze-bernsteins-killing-parents-turn-alleged-hate/story?id=59754707|title=1 year after Blaze Bernstein's killing, parents look to turn alleged hate crime into 'movement of hope'|last=|first=|date=December 30, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> ADL also drafted the model hate crimes legislation in the 1980s; it serves a model for the legislation that a majority of states have adopted.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/hate-crime-laws-dont-prevent-violence-against-lgbt-people/|title=Hate Crime Laws Don't Prevent Violence Against LGBT People: So why do many LGBT people, and others, feel so deeply about the need to have them?|journal=The Nation|date=October 2, 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|last1=Bronski|first1=Michael|last2=Pellegrini|first2=Ann|last3=Amico|first3=Michael}}</ref>\n\n=== Online content moderation / fighting cyberhate ===\nAs part of its goal of opposing anti-Semitism, ADL has founded the \"Center for Technology and Society\" to target online harassment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-for-technology-and-society|title=Center for Technology and Society|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> The goal of this center is to combat cyberbullying through research, education, and active intervention via industry and law-enforcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-for-technology-and-society/about|title=About the Center for Technology and Society|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> The ADL has participated in [[YouTube]]'s Trusted Flagger program, and has encouraged YouTube to remove videos which they flag as hate speech, citing the need to \"fight against terrorist use of online resources and cyberhate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-applauds-google-and-youtube-in-expanding-initiative-to-fight-online-hate|title=ADL Applauds Google and YouTube in Expanding Initiative to Fight Online Hate|website=ADL.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2019/06/05/adl-praises-youtube-for-decision-to-remove-racist-extremist-content/|title=ADL Praises YouTube for Decision to Remove Racist, Extremist Content|website=Algemeiner}}</ref> CTS is also playing a lead role working with the online game industry to fight white supremacist activity on platforms connected with gaming.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/07/25/anti-defamation-league-65-of-gamers-have-experienced-severe-harassment-in-online-games/|title=Anti-Defamation League: 65% of gamers have suffered severe harassment online|last=|first=|date=July 26, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/two-thirds-of-us-online-gamers-have-experienced-severe-harassment-new-adl-study|title=Two-Thirds of U.S. Online Gamers Have Experienced Severe Harassment, New ADL Study Finds|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n\nADL supports [[Israel]] as a [[Jewish and democratic state]],<ref>[https://www.adl.org/resources/fact-sheets/response-to-common-inaccuracy-israel-cant-be-jewish-democratic Response To Common Inaccuracy: Israel Can't be Jewish & Democratic], Anti-Defamation League.</ref> and supports a [[two-state solution]] to the [[Israeli-Palestinian conflict]], negotiated by the parties.<ref>[https://www.adl.org/education/resources/fact-sheets/response-to-common-inaccuracy-bi-national-one-state-solution Response To Common Inaccuracy: Bi-National/One-State Solution], Anti-Defamation League.</ref> The organization vociferously opposed the [[UN General Assembly Resolution 3379|1975 United Nations resolution]] ([[UN General Assembly Resolution 4686|revoked in 1991]]) which equated [[Zionism]] with racism,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/durban/adl_quotes.asp |title=U.N. World Conference Against Racism |publisher=ADL}}</ref> and attempts to revive that formulation at the 2001 U.N. [[World Conference Against Racism]] in [[Durban]], [[South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/durban/un_anti-zionism.asp |title=U.N. World Conference Against Racism |publisher=ADL}}</ref> ADL also has expressed concern over Israeli legislative proposals that would stifle freedom of expression and undermine Israeli democracy.<ref>[http://www.adl.org/press-center/press-releases/israel-middle-east/adl-concerned-that-proposed-legislation-on-ngo-funding.html ADL 'Concerned That Proposed Legislation on NGO Funding in Israel Would Erode Nation's Democratic Character,'] Anti-Defamation League January 11, 2016:'In 2011, the League urged the Israeli government to work to modify two similar bills regarding donations from foreign governments to Israeli NGOs, and voiced concern over laws that stifle free expression.'</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/reform-joins-adl-ajc-in-opposing-israels-ngo-bill/|title=Reform joins ADL, AJC in opposing Israel's NGO bill|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nWhile ADL was a lead supporter of Congressional legislation prohibiting US individuals and businesses from joining \"unsanctioned boycotts\" such as the 1970s [[Arab League boycott of Israel|Arab League Boycott]] against Israel,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/glossary-terms/arab-economic-boycott|title=Arab Economic Boycott|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> it has taken a different, case-by-case approach to state anti-boycott laws more recently enacted in response to the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|BDS movement]]. Several of these laws, which seek to prohibit State agencies and instrumentalities from investing in companies that boycott Israel and from entering into contracts with entities that boycott Israel, have been successfully challenged in the courts. The legal challenges have primarily been brought by the [[American Civil Liberties Union|ACLU]] and [[Council on American\u2013Islamic Relations|CAIR]] on First Amendment constitutional grounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/26/us/texas-bds-law/index.html|title=Texas has a law that says contractors can't boycott Israel. But a federal judge just blocked it|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/blog/free-speech/arizona-lawmakers-running-scared-after-anti-boycott-law-ruled-unconstitutional|title=Arizona Lawmakers Running Scared After Anti-Boycott Law Ruled Unconstitutional|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL generally has not publicly supported laws it felt were constitutionally suspect under the First Amendment, both for legal reasons and because the organization believed that such laws, even if what ADL describes as \"well-intentioned,\" were not an effective means of combating the BDS movement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-urges-texas-city-to-remove-no-israel-boycott-requirement-from-aid|title=ADL Urges Texas City to Remove 'No Israel Boycott' Requirement from Aid Application|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> However, as a general matter the organization also has not publicly opposed such state laws, preferring to work behind the scenes to try to make such laws less infirm under the Constitution or to propose non-binding resolutions opposing BDS. A possible division of internal views in ADL was disclosed when the liberal Jewish news media organization, [[The Forward]], published ostensibly leaked internal ADL staff memos dating from 2016 that opposed the anti-boycott laws.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/news/416030/revealed-secret-adl-memo-slammed-anti-bds-laws-as-harmful-to-jews/|title=REVEALED: Secret ADL Memo Slammed Anti-BDS Laws As 'Harmful' To Jews|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL did not comment directly on the leaked memos, but the statement it issued in response appeared to acknowledge that there had been, if were not still, sharply divided views within the organization and that it did not try to suppress internal robust discussion.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nADL has publicly stated that it believes that certain founders and leaders of the BDS movement are antisemitic, but has noted that many supporters of BDS, both Jewish and non-Jewish, are not antisemitic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/backgrounders/bds-the-global-campaign-to-delegitimize-israel|title=BDS: The Global Campaign to Delegitimize Israel|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nADL has condemned the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]]'s (UNHRC)  list of companies doing business with Jewish settlements in Israeli-run territories (West Bank, East Jerusalem, Golan Heights), issued in February 2020, calling it a \"blacklist.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.com/news/world/310631/unhrc-releases-blacklist-of-companies-conducting-business-in-israeli-settlements/|title=UNHRC Releases 'Blacklist' of Companies Conducting Business in Israeli Settlements|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-strongly-condemns-un-councils-blacklist-of-israeli-companies|title=ADL Strongly Condemns U.N. Council's Blacklist of Israeli Companies|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, ADL condemned Senate Republicans in the United States for attempting to ban [[same-sex marriage]] with the [[Federal Marriage Amendment]], and called the proposal discriminatory.<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Welcomes Demise Of Same-Sex Marriage Amendment; Expresses 'Dismay' At Senate Vote |publisher=ADL |date=June 7, 2006 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/DiRaB_41/4832_41.htm}}</ref> That same year, the ADL warned that the debate over [[illegal immigration]] was drawing [[neo-nazis]] and [[anti-Semites]] into the ranks of the [[The Minuteman Project Inc.|Minutemen Project]].\n\nIn 2010, during a hearing for Florida House Bill 11 (Crimes Against Homeless Persons), which was to revise the list of offenses judged to be [[Hate crime laws in the United States|hate crimes]] in Florida by adding a person's homeless status,<ref>{{cite web\n| title = flhouse.gov HB 11 \u2013 Crimes Against Homeless Persons\n| url = http://flhouse.gov/Sections/Bills/billsdetail.aspx?BillId=42143&\n| accessdate = April 22, 2010\n}}</ref> the League lobbied against the bill, which subsequently passed in the House by a vote of 80 to 28 and was sent to the Senate,<ref>{{cite web\n| title = flhouse.gov HB 11 Apr 20 2010 \u2013 Voting record Florida House of Representatives\n| url = http://flhouse.gov/Sections/Bills/floorvote.aspx?VoteId=10836&BillId=42143&\n| accessdate = April 22, 2010\n}}</ref> taking the position that adding more categories to the list would dilute the effectiveness of the law, which already includes race, religion, sexual orientation, disability, and age.<ref>{{cite web\n| title = Homeless could be added to Florida's hate crimes law\n| url = http://www.miamiherald.com/2010/04/21/1589541/homeless-could-be-added-to-floridas.html\n| accessdate = April 22, 2010\n}} ''Miami Herald'', Miami Herald Media Co., April 21, 2010, by Lee Logan, Tallahassee Bureau: \"During a committee hearing on the bill, the Anti-Defamation League spoke against the bill, arguing that adding more categories to the hate crimes law would dilute its effect. But lawmakers were swayed by arguments in favor of protecting the homeless.\"</ref>\n\nWhen the [[anti-Mormon]] film ''[[The God Makers]]'' (1982) was produced, Rhonda M. Abrams, Central Pacific (San Francisco) Regional Director for ADL, wrote a critical review, including the following statement:\n\n{{quote|Had a similar movie been made with either Judaism or Catholicism as its target, it would be immediately denounced for the scurrilous piece that it is. I sincerely hope that people of all faiths will similarly repudiate ''The Godmakers'' as defamatory and untrue, and recognize it for what it truly represents - a challenge to the religious liberty of all.<ref>[http://www.fairmormon.org/perspectives/publications/the-truth-about-the-god-makers/ia Letter to Dr. Richard Lindsay], Director of Public Communications, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, May 25, 1984</ref>}}\n\nADL supports [[Comprehensive Immigration Reform Act of 2007|Comprehensive]] and [[DREAM Act]] legislation that would provide conditional permanent residency to certain illegal aliens of good moral character who graduate from U.S. high schools, arrived in the United States as minors, and lived in the country continuously for at least five years prior to the bill's enactment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Afirman que con el debate de reforma migratoria subieron los cr\u00edmenes de odio|publisher=EFE News Services|date=January 25, 2013|quote= La Liga Antidifamaci\u00f3n Jud\u00eda ( ADL ) asegur\u00f3 hoy que desde que se inici\u00f3 el debate sobre una reforma migratoria integral en Estados Unidos se ha registrado un aumento de los cr\u00edmenes de odio contra los hispanos. ... Por su parte, el director del Departamento de Asuntos Legales de ADL, Steven Freeman, dijo a Efe que esta organizaci\u00f3n aboga por una reforma migratoria integral y el Dream Act}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, ADL condemned remarks by [[Ovadia Yosef]] that the sole purpose of non-Jews was to serve the Jews.<ref>Mozgovaya, Natasha. \"[http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/adl-slams-shas-spiritual-leader-for-saying-non-jews-were-born-to-serve-jews-1.320235?localLinksEnabled=false ADL slams Shas spiritual leader for saying non-Jews 'were born to serve Jews'].\" Haaretz Service. October 20, 2010.</ref>\n\nADL has spoken out against [[McCarthyism]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Norwood|first1=Stephen Harlan|last2=Pollack|first2=Eunice G.|title=Encyclopedia of American Jewish History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IB3mBsgfIHQC&pg=PA245|year=2008|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-85109-638-1|page=245}}</ref>\n\nADL has supported some moves of the Trump Administration, and criticized others. For example, the organization welcomed President Trump moving the U.S. Embassy to Jerusalem, thereby underscoring that Jerusalem was the capitol of Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-welcomes-president-trumps-announcement-on-jerusalem-calls-for-focus-on|title=ADL Welcomes President Trump's Announcement on Jerusalem; Calls for Focus on Peace Negotiations and Reducing Tensions|last=|first=|date=December 6, 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> ADL CEO and National Director Jonathan Greenblatt traveled to Israel to join Trump administration officials at the official opening ceremony of the embassy in Jerusalem.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-celebrates-historic-milestone-as-us-embassy-opens-in-jerusalem|title=ADL Celebrates 'Historic Milestone' as U.S. Embassy Opens in Jerusalem|last=|first=|date=May 14, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> ADL has also called for key Trump Administration executive Stephen Miller, the architect of the Trump administration policies on immigration, to be fired and condemned him as a white supremacist.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Relations with religious and ethnic groups ==\n\n=== Relations with Arabs and Muslims ===\n{{See also|Projects working for peace among Israelis and Arabs}}\n\nIn 2012, ADL released a statement opposing groups like the [[Stop Islamization of America]] and [[Stop Islamization of Europe]], and activists such as [[Pamela Geller]] and [[David Yerushalmi]], describing them as \"anti-Muslim bigots\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/article/stop-islamization-of-america-sioa|title=Stop Islamization of America (SIOA)|website=Anti-Defamation League}}</ref>\n\nSince U.S. Reprentatives [[Rashida Tlaib]] (D-MI) and [[Ilhan Omar]] (D-MN) were elected to the U.S. House of Representatives in late 2018, becoming in 2019 the first two Muslim women to serve in the U.S. Congress,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5445303/ilhan-omar-rashida-tlaib-midterm/|title=Ilhan Omar and Rashida Tlaib Just Became the First Muslim Women Elected to Congress|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL at times has defended them from racist and [[Islamophobia|Islamaphobic]] attacks,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JGreenblattADL/status/1102207176746156035|title=Tweet from ADL CEO Jonathan Greenblatt|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> as well as from what ADL has viewed as partisan efforts to weaponize accusations of antisemitism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitchy.com/brettt-3136/2019/05/13/adl-ceo-says-its-unacceptable-for-elected-officials-to-weaponize-rashida-tlaibs-comments/|title=ADL CEO says it's unacceptable for elected officials to 'weaponize' Rashida Tlaib's comments|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Indeed, Rep. Omar's \"inspiring\" story, as the first Somali-American lawmaker, was included in a book commissioned by ADL. ''The Good Fight,'' published before Rep. Omar's election to Congress, tells the stories of Americans who have fought for equality''.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ADL/status/943186695666708481|title=ADL Tweet, December 19, 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegoodfightbook.org/|title=Publishers' blurbs for \"The Good Fight\"|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Since their election to Congress, however, ADL also has repeatedly and harshly criticized Reps. Omar and Tlaib<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-statement-concerning-rep-rashida-tlaibs-tweet-on-pending-bds-bill-in|title=ADL Statement Concerning Rep. Rashida Tlaib's Tweet on Pending BDS Bill in Congress|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-calls-on-house-leadership-to-take-action-after-rep-omars-anti-semitic|title=ADL Calls on House Leadership to Take Action After Rep. Omar's Anti-Semitic Tweets|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freebeacon.com/politics/adl-rejects-omars-good-faith-defense-asks-pelosi-to-condemn-anti-semitic-rhetoric/|title=ADL Rejects Omar's 'Good Faith' Defense, Asks Pelosi to Condemn Anti-Semitic Rhetoric|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> for what it deemed to be antisemitic remarks and the spreading of dangerous antisemitic tropes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/jan/28/rashida-tlaib-responds-after-adl-accuses-her-of-sp/|title=Rep. Rashida Tlaib responds after ADL accuses her of spreading anti-Semitic 'blood libel'|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Relations with African-Americans ===\nIn 1997, the National Center for Black-Jewish Relations of [[Dillard University]], a [[historically black college|historically black university]] in [[New Orleans]], awarded the director of ADL, Abraham H. Foxman, with its first Annual [[Martin Luther King, Jr]].\u2013Donald R. Mintz Freedom and Justice Award.\n\nIn 2004, ADL became the lead partner in the Peace and Diversity Academy, a new New York City public high school with predominantly black and Hispanic students. In celebration of [[Black History Month]], the ADL created and distributed lesson plans to middle and high school teachers about [[Shirley Chisholm]] (1924\u20132005), the first black woman elected to the [[US Congress]], and an important civil rights leader.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nADL has also publicly accused a number of prominent African Americans of being anti-Semitic:\n\n* ADL has catalogued a more than three-decade history of [[Nation of Islam]] leader [[Louis Farrakhan]]'s espousal of anti-Semitic rhetoric such as claims that certain Jews are \"not real Jews\" and that they are \"wicked deceivers of the American people\" who \"sucked [Americans'] blood\", and that powerful Jews promote homosexuality and control black leadership.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/special_reports/farrakhan_own_words2/farrakhan_own_words.asp |title=Farrakhan In His Own Words |publisher=ADL}}</ref> Farrakhan first attracted the attention of the ADL with comments in a March 11, 1984, radio broadcast saying that, \"[[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] was a very great man\".<ref name=\"finalcall\">{{cite journal |title=Farrakhan and the Jewish Rift; How It All Started |journal=[[The Final Call]] |url=http://www.finalcall.com/perspectives/rift.html}}</ref> Farrakhan insists that he was using the word 'great' in the sense of 'Great Depression' or 'great white shark'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.noi.org/judaism-religion/|title=Minister Farrakhan rebuts fraudulent \"Judaism is a Gutter Religion\" canard|date=August 5, 2010|publisher=}}</ref> and on June 24, 1984, he described the Jewish state as \"structured on injustice, thievery, lying and deceit and using the name of God to shield your dirty religion under His holy and righteous name.\"<ref name=\"finalcall\" /> ADL has urged various groups including the [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People|NAACP]] (whose leader [[Benjamin Chavis]] developed a working relationship with Farrakhan in 1994) to dissociate themselves from Farrakhan and his views.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Foxman |first=Abraham H. |authorlink=Abraham Foxman |date=July 20, 1994 |title=Today's N.A.A.C.P. Draws on History; Set Farrakhan Aside |journal=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9503E7DE143EF933A15754C0A962958260}}</ref>\n* In 1984 ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' reported that then-ADL national director Nathan Perlmutter said that Rev. [[Jesse Jackson]], Sr. was anti-Semitic, after Jackson referred to New York City as \"Hymietown\".<ref>{{cite journal |date=February 23, 1984 |title=Post Reaffirms Report On Jackson Comment |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=13 |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0E10FB3B5D0C708EDDAB0894DC484D81}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |date=February 27, 1984 |title=Jackson Admits Saying 'Hymie' And Apologizes At A Synagogue |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=16 |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F30A14F83C5D0C748EDDAB0894DC484D81}}</ref> However, ADL later reconciled with Jackson and has worked with him on the issue of the Iranian Jewish community.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Rev. Jesse Jackson Meets with Iranian Jewish Families Pledges to Intercede on Behalf of Imprisoned Jews |publisher=ADL |date=June 11, 1999 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/ASInt_13/3401_13.asp}}</ref>\n* Film Director [[Spike Lee]] was criticized by the Anti-Defamation League for his portrayal of Jewish nightclub owners Moe and Josh Flatbush in his film ''[[Mo' Better Blues]]'' (1990). The Anti-Defamation League said that the characterizations of the nightclub owners \"dredge up an age-old and highly dangerous form of anti-Semitic stereotyping\", and it was \"disappointed that Spike Lee \u2013 whose success is largely due to his efforts to break down racial stereotypes and prejudice \u2013 has employed the same kind of tactics that he supposedly deplores\".<ref>{{cite journal |date=August 16, 1990 |title=Spike Lee's Jews and the Passage From Benign Cliche Into Bigotry|journal=[[The New York Times]] |author=Caryn James|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/08/16/movies/critic-s-notebook-spike-lee-s-jews-passage-benign-cliche-into-bigotry.html}}</ref> Lee's portrayal also angered the B'nai B'rith and other such Jewish organizations, causing Lee to apologize via an Opinion-Editorial article in ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |date=August 13, 2006 |title=The Angriest Auteur|journal=[[New York Magazine]] |author=Ariel Levy|url=http://nymag.com/movies/profiles/19144/}}</ref>\n* During the 2002 election cycle, ADL, in a letter to ''The New York Times'', harshly criticized [[Congressional Black Caucus]] member [[Cynthia McKinney]] of Georgia for launching attacks perceived as racial against her Jewish opponent. According to an August 19, 2002, article in ''The New York Times'', ADL Director Abraham Foxman said, \"It made sense that Jewish Americans would want to contribute to efforts to replace Ms. McKinney\".\n* In February 2005, ADL National Director Abraham Foxman called it hypocritical for hip-hop producer [[Russell Simmons]] to lead an ad campaign against anti-Semitism while, in Foxman's view, also defending or excusing Louis Farrakhan's anti-Semitic statements.<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Calls on Russell Simmons to Distance Himself from Minister Farrakhan |publisher=ADL |date=February 14, 2005 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/ASUS_12/4645_12.htm}}</ref> Later that year ADL urged prominent black leaders including Simmons to reconsider their support for Farrakhan and [[Malik Zulu Shabazz]] organizing the [[Millions More Movement]] and to \"stand up\" against black anti-Semitism.<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Urges Prominent African-American Leaders to Reconsider Their Support for the \"Millions More Movement\" |publisher=ADL |date=May 2, 2005 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/ASUS_12/4707_12.htm}}</ref> Simmons, responding to ADL Director Abraham Foxman, said, \"simply put, you are misguided, arrogant, and very disrespectful of African Americans, and most importantly, your statements will unintentionally or intentionally lead to a negative impression of Jews in the minds of millions of African Americans\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.millionsmoremovement.com/news/russell-simmons05-09-2005.htm |title=Russell Simmons Responds to Abraham Foxman about the Millions More Movement |last=Simmons |first=Russell |authorlink=Russell Simmons |date=May 9, 2005 |publisher=[[Millions More Movement]]}}</ref> Foxman replied, \"If there were a Jewish event which was led by an out-and-out racist, I would expect Black leaders to say to me that ADL should have nothing to do with it. And I would agree with them, rather than condemn them for their action.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/media_watch/internet/20050510-Russell+Simmons.htm |title=Response to Russell Simmons |date=May 9, 2005 |publisher=ADL |access-date=March 16, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607153052/http://www.adl.org/media_watch/internet/20050510-Russell+Simmons.htm |archive-date=June 7, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Interfaith camp ===\nADL's New England Regional Office has also established a faith-based initiative called \"The Interfaith Youth Leadership Program\", better known as \"Camp If\", or Camp Interfaith. Involving teenagers of the Christian, Jewish, and Islamic faiths, the camp brings the teens together for a week at camp where the teens bond and learn about each other's cultures. The camp has emerged as a new attempt to foster good relations between younger members of the Abrahamic faiths.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Siek |first=Stephanie V. |date=April 6, 2006 |title=A different kind of camp |journal=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2006/04/06/a_different_kind_of_camp/}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n{{POV section|date=December 2018}}\n\n===Arab American and African American lawsuit against ADL===\nIn 1996, ADL settled a federal civil lawsuit filed by groups representing [[African Americans]] and [[Arab Americans]] that alleged that the ADL hired agents with police ties to gather information. ADL did not admit any wrongdoing, but agreed to a restraining injunction barring ADL from obtaining information from state employees who are forbidden by law to divulge such information. ADL also agreed to contribute $25,000 to a fund that funds inter-community relationship projects, and cover the plaintiffs' legal costs of $175,000.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1996-09-04/news/mn-40507_1_anti-defamation-league Anti-Defamation League Settles Lawsuit by Civil Rights Groups], LA Times, 4 September 1996</ref><ref>[https://www.jta.org/1996/09/06/archive/adl-to-pay-200000-to-settle-suit-alleging-spying-activities ADL to Pay $200,000 to Settle Suit Alleging Spying Activities], JTA, 6 September 1996</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QM1hloeMQqgC&pg=PA96&lpg=PA96&dq=%22Anti-Defamation+League%22+settlement+1996&source=bl&ots=d1L3G8qgX8&sig=Auo9IfPqSIcVRuL2g7zlDpFJTF4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjO5Y7Pr7XfAhWQDuwKHeNbB1MQ6AEwC3oECAIQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Anti-Defamation%20League%22%20settlement%201996&f=false American Jewish Year, Book 1998], page 96</ref>\n\n=== Armenian Genocide controversy ===\n{{Undue weight section|date=February 2019}}\nIn 2007, Abraham Foxman came under criticism for his stance on the [[Armenian Genocide]]. ADL had previously described it as a \"massacre\" and an \"atrocity,\" but not as a \"genocide.\"<ref name=\"http\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/Mise_00/5114_00.htm\n|title=ADL Statement on the Armenian Genocide\n|date=August 21, 2007}}</ref> Foxman had earlier opposed calls for the U.S. Government to recognise it as a \"genocide.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewcy.com/feature/2007-07-09/fire_foxman |title=Fire Foxman: Denying the Armenian Genocide should be the last atrocity perpetrated by the ADL chief.}}</ref> In early August 2007, complaints about the Anti-Defamation League's refusal to acknowledge the [[Armenian Genocide]] led to [[Watertown, Massachusetts]]'s, unanimous town council decision to end its participation in ADL's \"No Place for Hate\" campaign. (Watertown is known for its Armenian population.) In the subsequent months, some [[human rights]] commissions in other Massachusetts communities decided to follow Watertown's lead and withdraw from the ADL's No Place for Hate anti-discrimination program.<ref name=\"Woolhouse\">{{cite news|last=Woolhouse|first=Megan|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/12/05/adls_regional_leader_resigns/|title=ADL's regional leader resigns: Backers cite rift on genocide issue|date=December 5, 2007|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Esker/medford@cnc.com|first=Sharon Tosto|url=http://medford.wickedlocal.com/x96464381|title=City recognizes Armenian genocide, suspends ADL membership|work=Medford Transcript|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en}}</ref>  ADL had earlier received direct pressure from the Turkish Foreign ministry.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.co.il/hasite/spages/911393.html \u05d8\u05d5\u05e8\u05e7\u05d9\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc: \u05e2\u05d6\u05e8\u05d5 \u05dc\u05e0\u05d5 \u05dc\u05e2\u05e6\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d4\u05db\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d0\u05de\u05e8\u05d9\u05e7\u05d0\u05d9\u05ea \u05d1\u05e9\u05d5\u05d0\u05d4 \u05d4\u05d0\u05e8\u05de\u05e0\u05d9\u05ea] Haaretz, 10/10/07, Barak Ravid</ref> \n\nAlso in August 2007, an editorial in ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' criticized ADL by saying that, \"as an organization concerned about human rights, it ought to acknowledge the [[genocide]] against the Armenian people during [[World War I]], and criticize Turkish attempts to repress the memory of this historical reality.\"<ref>{{cite news |date= August 3, 2007 |url=http://www.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/editorials/articles/2007/08/03/a_genocide_not_to_be_denied/ |title=A genocide not to be denied |work=[[Boston Globe]]}}</ref> \n\nOn August 17, 2007, ADL fired its regional [[New England]] director, Andrew H. Tarsy, for breaking ranks with the main organization and for saying that ADL should recognize the genocide.<ref name=\"obrien\">{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/08/18/adl_local_leader_fired_on_armenian_issue/\n|title=ADL local leader fired on Armenian issue: Genocide question sparked bitter debate\n|work=The Boston Globe\n|first=Keith\n|last=O'Brien\n|date=August 18, 2007}}</ref> In an August 21, 2007, news release, ADL changed its position and acknowledged the genocide, but maintained its opposition to congressional resolutions aimed at recognizing it.<ref name=\"http\" /> Foxman wrote, \"the consequences of those actions,\" by the [[Ottoman Empire]] against Armenians, \"were indeed tantamount to genocide.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Brien|first=Keith|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/08/22/adl_chief_bows_to_critics/|title=ADL chief bows to critics: Foxman cites rift, calls Armenian deaths genocide|date=August 22, 2007|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The [[Turkish government]] condemned the league's statement.<ref>{{cite news|last=Levenson|first=Michael|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/08/24/turkey_condemns_statement_by_adl/|title=Turkey condemns statement by ADL|date=August 24, 2007|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> Tarsey subsequently won his job back,<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Brien|first=Keith|url=http://www.boston.com/news/globe/city_region/breaking_news/2007/08/antidefamation_1.html|title=Anti-Defamation League rehires New England director|date=September 7, 2007|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref>  but subsequently submitted his resignation, on December 4, 2007.<ref name=\"Woolhouse\" /> <ref>{{cite web\n |url          = http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/news/?content_id=4108\n |title        = Tarsy Resignation Draws Mixed Emotions From Area Colleagues\n |first        = Rachel\n |last         = Axelbank\n |publisher    = Jewish Advocate\n |date         = December 6, 2007\n |access-date  = January 7, 2008\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071210223450/http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/news/?content_id=4108\n |archive-date = December 10, 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nThe 2007 ADL \"Statement on the Armenian Genocide,\" was criticized by activists as failing to be a full, unequivocal acknowledgment of the [[Armenian genocide]], because the use of the qualifier \"tantamount\" was seen as inappropriate, and the use of the word \"consequences\" was seen as an attempt to circumvent the international legal definition of genocide by avoiding any language that would imply intent, a crucial aspect of the 1948 UN [[Genocide Convention]] definition.\n\nOn May 13, 2016, [[Jonathan Greenblatt]], then ADL's CEO and National Director for less than a year, published a blog post in which he wrote \"What happened to the Armenian people was unequivocally genocide\" and urged the U.S. to take a position recognizing the Armenian genocide.<ref>[[Jonathan Greenblatt|Greenblatt, Jonathan]] (May 13, 2016) [https://www.adl.org/blog/adl-on-the-armenian-genocide \"ADL on the Armenian Genocide\"] Anti-Defamation League website</ref>  In late 2019, ADL publicly endorsed and lobbied for a historic Congressional resolution commemorating the Armenian genocide, which passed the House of Representatives with bipartisan support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-endorses-congressional-resolution-commemorating-the-armenian-genocide|title=ADL Endorses Congressional Resolution Commemorating the Armenian Genocide|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/29/us/politics/armenian-genocide-resolution.html|title=House Passes Resolution Recognizing Armenian Genocide|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/12/us/politics/senate-armenian-genocide.html|title=Senate Passes Resolution Recognizing Armenian Genocide, in Defiance of Trump|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>  The U.S. Senate passed a similar resolution, which was also backed by ADL, but in December 2019 the Trump Administration, under pressure from Turkey's President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan|Recep Tayyip Erdogan]], refused to back recognition of the Armenian genocide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-armenian-genocide-erdogan-turkey-native-americans-a9250281.html|title=Trump refuses to back recognition of Armenian genocide after Erdogan threat|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Denver defamation suit ===\nIn 1994, ADL became embroiled in a dispute between neighbors in Denver, Colorado. Upon the involvement of ADL, the petty quarreling of next door neighbors, initially about garden plants and pets, quickly escalated into both civil and criminal court cases involving charges of anti-Semitism, and counter charges of defamation.\n\nCandace and Mitchell Aronson, Jewish next door neighbors of William and Dorothy Quigley, used a [[Radio Shack]] police scanner to listen in on the cordless telephone conversations of Mr. and Mrs. Quigley. When the Aronsons heard the Quigleys discuss a campaign to drive them from the neighborhood with \"Nazi scare tactics,\" the Aronsons contacted the Denver office of ADL. Upon the advice of ADL, the Aronsons then recorded the Quigley's private telephone conversations. The conversations included discussions of putting pictures of oven doors on the Aronsons' home (a reference to the Holocaust), burning one of the Aronson children, and wishing that the Aronsons had been killed in a suicide bombing. (The Quigleys later indicated that these remarks were not anti-Semitic, and were only intended to be sick humor.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/13674/edition_id/264/format/html/displaystory.html|title=Jewish News Weekly|publisher=}}</ref> Neither the Aronsons nor ADL were aware that Congress had amended federal wiretap law which made it illegal to record conversations from a cordless telephone, to transcribe the material, and to use the transcriptions for any purpose.\n\nNot knowing about the new federal law, the Aronsons used the tapes as the basis for a federal civil lawsuit against the Quigleys in December 1994. A day later, Saul Rosenthal, Regional Director of ADL, appeared at a news conference with the Aronsons in which he described their encounter with the Quigleys as \"a vicious anti-Semitic campaign,\" based solely on conversations he and associates had with the Aronsons. Later that day, Mr. Rosenthal expanded on his remarks in an interview on a Denver radio talk show.\n\nTwo days later, Jefferson County prosecutors used the tapes as the basis for filing criminal charges against the Quigleys.\n\nThe Quigleys became the target of scorn and ridicule. They received threats, and were forced to hire security guards for their home. A package of dog feces was mailed to their house. When they attended church, their priest openly chastised them in his sermon. The family was forced to shop in other towns, to avoid being recognized.<ref>{{cite web|title=Quigley v. Rosenthall|url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-10th-circuit/1360107.html|website=Findlaw|publisher=Findlaw|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref> Mr. Quigley's career with [[United Artists]] suffered serious damage.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lane|first1=George|title=Charges of bigotry backfire|url=http://extras.denverpost.com/news/news0429.htm|accessdate=June 23, 2015|issue=April 29, 2000|newspaper=Denver Post}}</ref>\n\nUpon investigation, and after assistant district attorney Steven Jensen heard on the tapes the context of Mrs. Quigley's remarks, all charges but one, a misdemeanor traffic violation against Mr. Quigley, were dropped. The district attorney issued two letters of apology to the Quigleys, saying he found no evidence that either had engaged in \"anti-Semitic conduct or harassment.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/05/13/us/privacy-rights-win-over-bias-charges-in-defamation-case.html | work=The New York Times | title=Privacy Rights Win Over Bias Charges In Defamation Case | date=May 13, 2000}}</ref>\n\nThe Quigleys brought a lawsuit against ADL, Rosenthal, the Aronsons, and two ADL volunteer attorneys. The two attorneys agreed to pay $350,000 to the Quigleys in settlement of their claims. The Quigley settlement with the Aronsons did not involve a cash payment. The Quigleys maintained their action against ADL and Rosenthal, which was heard in federal court. A federal jury returned a verdict of $10 million in favor of the Quigleys. ADL appealed.\n\nAccording to an April 13, 2001, article in ''[[The Forward]]'', upon hearing the appeal, a federal judge \"lambasted the ADL for labeling a nasty neighborhood feud as an anti-Semitic event\" and upheld most of Quigley's $10 million [[lawsuit]] for [[slander and libel|defamation]]. According to a report in the ''[[Rocky Mountain News]]'', with accrued interest, the judgment amounted to more than $12 million.<ref>{{cite news  |title=ADL Pays More Than $12 Million to Former Evergreen Couple |date=March 12, 2004 |newspaper=Rocky Mountain News |last=Abbott |first=Karen}}</ref>\n\n=== New antisemitism controversy ===\n{{Main|New antisemitism}}\nA book entitled ''The [[New Anti-Semitism]]'' (New York, 1974) by ADL national leaders Arnold Forster and Benjamin R. Epstein argued that a new kind of anti-Semitism is on the rise. A subsequent book, ''The Real Anti-Semitism in America'' (New York, 1982) was written by ADL national leader Nathan Perlmutter and his wife, Ruth Ann Perlmutter. In ''Never Again? The Threat of the New Anti-Semitism'' (San Francisco, 2003), by ADL's national director Abraham Foxman, he states on page 4: \"We currently face as great a threat to the safety and security of the Jewish people as the one we faced in the 1930s\u2014if not a greater one.\"<ref name=\"adl.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/Anti_semitism/never_again.asp |title=Never Again? The Threat of the New Anti-Semitism |publisher=ADL}}</ref>\n\nReviewing Forster and Epstein's work in a May 1974 issue of ''[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]'', Earl Raab, founding director of the Nathan Perlmutter Institute for Jewish Advocacy at [[Brandeis University]], argued that a \"new anti-Semitism\" was indeed emerging in America, in the form of opposition to the collective rights of the Jewish people, but he criticized Forster and Epstein for conflating it with anti-Israel bias.<ref>Raab, Earl. \"Is there a New Anti-Semitism?\", ''Commentary'', May 1974, pp. 53\u201354.</ref> Allan Brownfeld writes that Forster and Epstein's new definition of antisemitism trivialized the concept by turning it into \"a form of political blackmail\" and \"a weapon with which to silence any criticism of either Israel or U.S. policy in the Middle East,\"<ref>{{cite journal\n  |title = Anti-Semitism: Its Changing Meaning\n  |last = Brownfeld\n  |first = Allan\n  |journal = [[Journal of Palestine Studies]]\n  |publisher = [[Institute for Palestine Studies]]\n  |issn = 1533-8614\n  |volume = 16\n  |issue = 3\n  |year = 1987\n  |pages = 53\u201367\n  |doi = 10.2307/2536789\n  |jstor = 2536789\n  }}</ref> while Edward S. Shapiro, in ''A Time for Healing: American Jewry Since World War II'', has written that, \"Forster and Epstein implied that the new anti-Semitism was the inability of Gentiles to love Jews and Israel enough.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Shapiro|first=Edward S.|title=A Time for Healing: American Jewry Since World War II|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|year=1992|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780801843471/page/47 47]|isbn=0-8018-4347-2|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780801843471/page/47}}</ref>\n\n[[Norman Finkelstein]] has written that organizations such as the Anti-Defamation League have brought forward charges of new anti-Semitism at various intervals since the 1970s, \"not to fight antisemitism, but rather to exploit the historical suffering of Jews in order to immunize Israel against criticism.\"<ref name=Finkelstein21>{{cite book|last=Finkelstein|first=Norman|title=Beyond Chutzpah: On the Misuse of Anti-Semitism and the Abuse of History|publisher=University of California Press|year=2005|pages=21\u201322}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' has reported that the ADL has repeatedly accused Finkelstein of being a \"[[Holocaust denial|Holocaust denier]],\" and that \"these charges have proved baseless.\"<ref name=\"WP sparks\">{{cite journal |last=Powell |first=Michael |date=October 9, 2006 |title=In N.Y., Sparks Fly Over Israel Criticism |journal=[[The Washington Post]] |pages=A03 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/08/AR2006100800817.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Park51 Community Center controversy ===\nOn July 28, 2010, ADL issued a statement in which it expressed opposition to the [[Park51]] Community Center, a proposed Islamic community center and mosque near the [[World Trade Center site]] in New York. ADL stated, \"The controversy which has emerged regarding the building of a Community Center at this location is counterproductive to the healing process. Therefore, under these unique circumstances, we believe the City of New York would be better served if an alternative location could be found.\"<ref name=\"berk\" /> ADL denounced what it saw as bigoted attacks on the project. Foxman opined that some of those who oppose the mosque are \"bigots,\" and that the plan's proponents may have every right to build the mosque at that location. Nevertheless, he said that building the mosque at that site would unnecessarily cause more pain for families of some victims of 9/11.<ref name=\"berk\">Jacob Berkman, [http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2010/07/30/2740283/adl-opposes-world-trade-center-mosque ADL opposes World Trade Center Mosque] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100803005159/http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2010/07/30/2740283/adl-opposes-world-trade-center-mosque |date=August 3, 2010 }}, [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]], July 30, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jacoby |first=Susan |url=http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/spirited_atheist/2010/08/ground_zero_mosque_protected_by_first_amendment--but_its_still_salt_in_a_wound.html |title=The Spirited Atheist: Ground Zero mosque protected by First Amendment \u2013 but it's still salt in a wound|newspaper=The Washington Post |date=August 6, 2010 |accessdate=April 24, 2015| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100817115334/http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/spirited_atheist/2010/08/ground_zero_mosque_protected_by_first_amendment--but_its_still_salt_in_a_wound.html| archivedate= August 17, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes6\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/05/opinion/l05mosque.html | work=The New York Times | title=The ADL, the Mosque and the Fight Against Bigotry | date=August 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.adl.org/PresRele/CvlRt_32/5820_32.htm \"Statement On Islamic Community Center Near Ground Zero\"], Anti-Defamation League, July 28, 2010.</ref>\n\nThis opposition to the Community Center led to criticism of the statement from various parties, including one ADL board member, the [[American Jewish Committee]], the [[Jewish Community Relations Council|Jewish Community Relations Council of New York]], Rabbi [[Irwin Kula]], columnists [[Jeffrey Goldberg]] and [[Peter Beinart]], the [[Interfaith Alliance]],<ref>Adam Dickter, [http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/new_york/wake_adl_jewish_groups_back_ground_zero_mosque \"In Wake Of ADL, Jewish Groups Back Ground Zero Mosque\"], ''[[The Jewish Week]]'', August 3, 2010.</ref> and the [[Shalom Center]].<ref>Grace Rauh, [http://manhattan.ny1.com/content/top_stories/123265/jewish-leaders-rally-in-support-of-wtc-mosque/ \"Jewish Leaders Rally In Support Of WTC Mosque\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816033945/http://manhattan.ny1.com/content/top_stories/123265/jewish-leaders-rally-in-support-of-wtc-mosque |date=August 16, 2010 }}, ''[[NY1]]'', August 5, 2010.</ref> In an interview with ''[[The New York Times]]'' Abe Foxman published a statement in reaction to criticism.<ref>Abraham H. Foxman, [http://www.adl.org/ADL_Opinions/Interfaith/Mosque_Ground_Zero.htm \"The Mosque at Ground Zero\"], originally published in ''[[Huffington Post]]'', August 2, 2010.</ref> In protest of ADL's stance, [[CNN]] host [[Fareed Zakaria]] returned the Hubert H. Humphrey First Amendment Freedoms Prize ADL awarded him in 2005.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2010/US/08/07/new.york.zakaria.adl/ CNN host returns ADL award over stance on Islamic center], [[CNN]], August 9, 2010.</ref> ADL chair Robert G. Sugarman responded to a critical ''[[The New York Times]]'' editorial<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/04/opinion/04wed1.html A Monument to Tolerance], ''[[The New York Times]]'' editorial, August 3, 2010.</ref> writing, \"we have publicly taken on those who criticized the mosque in ways that reflected anti-Muslim bigotry or used the controversy for that purpose\" and stating that ADL has combated [[Islamophobia]].<ref>Robert G. Sugarman, [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/05/opinion/l05mosque.html \"Letter to New York Times\"] (August 4, 2010) ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU)\n*[[American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee]]\n*[[Antisemitism in the United States]]\n*[[Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations]]\n* ''[[Defamation (film)|Defamation]]'' (Documentary movie by [[Yoav Shamir]])\n*[[Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation]]\n*[[Israel lobby in the United States]]\n*[[Jewish Council for Public Affairs]]\n*[[Jews Against Anti-Christian Defamation]]\n*[[Membership discrimination in California social clubs]]\n*[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]\n*[[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.adl.org Official Website]\n\n{{Anti-Defamation League|state=expanded}}\n{{Antisemitism topics|state=collapsed}}\n{{Organized Jewish Life in the United States}}\n{{World Jewish Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Anti-Defamation League| ]]\n[[Category:1913 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Anti-racist organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish anti-racism]]\n[[Category:Jewish organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish political organizations]]\n[[Category:Opposition to antisemitism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1913]]\n[[Category:Political advocacy groups in the United States]]\n[[Category:Civil liberties advocacy groups in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name         = Anti-Defamation League\n|image        = ADL logo (2018).svg\n|size         = 200px\n|motto        = Fighting Hate for Good\n|formation    = {{Start date and age|1913|09}} (as Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith)\n|founder      = [[Sigmund Livingston]]\n|headquarters = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|type         = [[Civil rights]] law\n|leader_title = Director\n|leader_name  = [[Jonathan Greenblatt]]\n|key_people   = Sigmund Livingston (Founder)<br />Robert G. Sugarman (Chairman)\n|website      = [http://www.adl.org/ www.adl.org/]\n}}\n{{Antisemitism}}\nThe '''Anti-Defamation League''' ('''ADL'''; formerly known as the '''Anti-Defamation League of [[B'nai B'rith]]''') is an international [[Jews|Jewish]] [[non-governmental organization]] based in the [[United States]]. It was founded in late September 1913 by the Independent Order of [[B'nai B'rith]], a [[Jews|Jewish]] [[service organization]]. ADL subsequently split from B'nai B'rith and continued as an independent U.S. Section 501(c)(3) nonprofit. In its 2017 annual information Form 990, ADL reported total revenues of just over $70 million, from contributions and grants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdf.guidestar.org/PDF_Images/2017/131/818/2017-131818723-1035a764-9.pdf|title=ANTI-DEFAMATION LEAGUE FORM 990|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nADL states that its mission is a dual one: \"To stop the defamation of the Jewish people, and to secure justice and fair treatment to all\" via the development of \"new programs, policies and skills to expose and combat whatever holds us back.\"<ref name=\"ADLCharter\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-mission|title=Our Mission|website=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> Opposing [[Antisemitism]] and extremism, ADL describes its \"ultimate goal\" as \"a world in which no group or individual suffers from bias, discrimination or hate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are|title=Who We Are|website=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe headquarters of ADL are located in [[New York City]]. [[Abraham Foxman]] was the national director from 1987 for more than a quarter century. In November 2014, it was announced that [[Jonathan Greenblatt]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/leadership/staff/jonathan-greenblatt|title=Jonathan Greenblatt, CEO and National Director|last=Anti-Defamation League|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> a serial social entrepreneur, former Silicon Valley tech executive and former Obama Administration official who had not operated within the Jewish communal organization world prior to his hiring, would succeed Foxman as national director in July 2015.<ref>[http://www.jta.org/2014/11/06/news-opinion/united-states/white-house-aide-to-succeed-abe-foxman-as-adl-chief-1 \"White House aide Jonathan Greenblatt to succeed Abe Foxman as ADL chief\"], ''[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]'', November 6, 2014.</ref> The national chair of the governing board of directors is Esta Gordon Epstein: she is the second woman to hold the organization's top volunteer leadership post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newengland.adl.org/news/longtime-adl-boston-leader-esta-epstein-named-chair-of-organizations-national-board/|title=LONGTIME ADL BOSTON LEADER ESTA GORDON EPSTEIN NAMED CHAIR OF ORGANIZATION'S NATIONAL BOARD|last=|first=|date=November 8, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>[http://www.adl.org/about-adl/adl-leadership.html Barry Curtiss-Lusher, National Chair] ADL.org, ''accessed November 9, 2014.''</ref> ADL has 25 regional offices in the United States<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/anti-semitism/anti-semitism-in-the-us|title=Anti-Semitism in the US|work=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019|quote=Through our network of 25 regional offices}}</ref> including a Government Relations Office in Washington DC, and is also active overseas, with an office in Israel and staff in Europe.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/anti-semitism/anti-semitism-globally|title=Anti-Semitism Globally|work=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nADL has been criticized both from the right<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/12/anti-defamation-league-trump-232049|title=ADL combats criticism of being too tough on Trump|last=|first=|date=January 1, 2016|website=Politico.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> and left of the U.S. political spectrum, including within the American Jewish community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/opinion/.premium-from-left-and-right-why-is-a-league-of-haters-descending-on-the-adl-1.6053744|title=Opinion From Left and Right, Why Is a League of Haters Descending on the ADL?|newspaper=Haaretz|date=May 3, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020|last1=Cohen|first1=Debra Nussbaum}}</ref> Some of the criticism from the left, or at least from the far left, is based on ADL's support for [[Israel]] as a Jewish homeland and the organization's vocal opposition to attempts to equate [[Zionism]], the national movement for a state for the Jewish people, with racism. Indeed, this stance has led some on the farther reaches of the American left (including some Jewish groups, such as [[Jewish Voice for Peace]]) to claim that so long as ADL continues to support Israel as a Jewish homeland, it cannot credibly call itself a civil rights organization, regardless of any other civil rights positions it takes domestically or internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.losangelesblade.com/2019/01/31/creating-change-2019-creates-controversy-again/|title=Creating Change 2019 creates controversy, again|last=|first=|date=January 31, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://droptheadl.wordpress.com/why-droptheadl/|title=#DropTheADL: Communities say NO to the Anti-Defamation League in our schools, coalitions, and movements|last=|first=|date=May 30, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther ADL positions and actions, past and present, that have generated criticism from the left include domestic spying allegations, its former stance on the [[Armenian Genocide]],<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|first1=Rupen|last1=Janbazian|accessdate=2019-09-25|title=ADL's Official Recognition of Armenian Genocide Ends Years-Long Controversy|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2016/05/16/adl-armenian-genocide-2016/|date=16 May 2016|website=The Armenian Weekly}}</ref> since repudiated and apologized for,<ref name=\":0\" /> and what frequently is alleged by the left to be ADL's conflation of opposition to Israel with [[antisemitism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/how-a-jewish-civil-rights-group-became-a-villain-on-the-far-left/|title=How a Jewish civil rights group became a villain on the far-left|last=Sales|first=Ben|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Shira|last1=Hanau|accessdate=2019-09-25|title=Can ADL Be A Moral Voice For Millennials?|url=https://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/can-adl-be-a-moral-voice-for-millennials/|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com}}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, rightwing groups and pundits, including very conservative Jewish groups, have attacked ADL, labeling it an arm of the Democratic party (presumably in part because its CEO, [[Jonathan Greenblatt]], was in the Obama administration)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/amari-sohrab/the-adl-smears-mike-pompeo/|title=The ADL Smears Mike Pompeo|last=Ahmari|first=Sohrab|date=April 19, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jns.org/opinion/whatever-happened-to-the-adl/|title=Whatever happened to the ADL?: The attack on Kavanaugh's nomination to the Supreme Court is the latest instance of how Jonathan Greenblatt has turned the venerable anti-Semitism watchdog into a partisan outfit.|last=Tobin|first=Jonathan|date=July 13, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> and decrying its civil rights agenda, which supports immigrants and refugees, trans rights and other [[LGBT|LGBTQ]] rights, and advocates against establishment of religion, as well as against [[Islamophobia|Islamaphobia]]. In mid 2018 ADL publicly raised concerns over President Donald Trump's nomination of then-DC Circuit Court of Appeals judge [[Brett Kavanaugh]] as an Associate Justice of the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-response-to-the-presidents-nomination-of-judge-brett-kavanaugh-to-serve-as|title=ADL Response to the President's Nomination of Judge Brett Kavanaugh to Serve as an Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court|last=|first=|date=July 9, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsmax.com/newsfront/brett-kavanaugh-scotus-adl-senate/2018/07/12/id/871445/|title=ADL 'Concerned' About Kavanaugh Nomination|last=Beamon|first=Todd|date=July 12, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/jewish-groups-slam-trump-s-supreme-court-nominee-kavanaugh-1.6264823|title=Jewish Groups Slam Trump's Supreme Court Nominee Kavanaugh|last=|first=|date=July 10, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>Despite the fact that ADL had for many years submitted questions to the Senate Judiciary Committee for Supreme Court and other key government nominations,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/media-watch/letter-to-the-wall-street-journal-regarding-criticism-of-adls-stance-on-judge|title=Letter to the Wall Street Journal Regarding Criticism of ADL's Stance on Judge Kavanaugh|last=Sugarman|first=Robert G.|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> the organization and CEO Jonathan Greenblatt were harshly criticized by many on the right for raising concerns in this instance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freebeacon.com/issues/anti-defamation-league-criticized-entering-partisan-kavanaugh-confirmation-fight/|title=Anti-Defamation League Criticized for Entering Partisan Kavanaugh Confirmation Fight|last=|first=|date=July 26, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, in another move that enraged many on the right, the ADL called for the resignation or firing of Trump administration official [[Stephen Miller (political advisor)|Stephen Miller]], the architect of the Administration's immigration policy, on the basis of his association with white supremacists.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/jewish-groups-stephen-miller-resign-white-nationalist_n_5dd69935e4b0e29d72800575?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly91cy5zZWFyY2gueWFob28uY29tLw&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAG5GoJ0dtOkPudr5tkzXMWY-wRmtd1nHDOfZ1c7WOW3gYQKtSQgDjZaIXDUnko0UMrEJVEYUXG3jMWrrsrV52jBKycFPCh7lje-saS6lbR17o5_4ikE4B7PIIACorUKfLxJXapH0BueU1WTMTER8dUqZKRH2Ep2TZ2Y83nmA0kDE|title=Jewish Groups Demand Stephen Miller Resign From White House|last=Mathias|first=Christopher|date=November 21, 2019|website=HuffPost|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Jewish-groups-again-call-for-Stephen-Miller-to-quit-614202|title=Jewish groups again call for Stephen Miller to quit|last=Kampeas|first=Ron|date=January 15, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Origin ==\nFounded in late September 1913 by [[B'nai B'rith]], with [[Sigmund Livingston]] as its first leader, the ADL's charter states, {{quote|The immediate object of the League is to stop, by appeals to reason and conscience and, if necessary, by appeals to law, the defamation of the Jewish people. Its ultimate purpose is to secure justice and fair treatment to all citizens alike and to put an end forever to unjust and unfair discrimination against and ridicule of any sect or body of citizens.<ref name=ADLCharter />}}\nThe Anti-Defamation League was founded by B'nai B'rith as a response to attacks on Jews; the recent conviction of [[Leo Frank]] was mentioned by [[Adolf Kraus]] when he announced the creation of ADL.<ref>{{cite book|last=Moore|first=Deborah Dash|title=B'nai B'rith and the Challenge of Ethnic Leadership|year=1981|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-87395-480-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/bnaibrithch00moor/page/108 108]|url=https://archive.org/details/bnaibrithch00moor/page/108}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Jews in American Politics: Essays|year=2001|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-7425-0181-2|page=105|author=Jerome A. Chanes|editor1=Louis S |editor2=y Maisel |editor3=Ira N. Forman |editor4=Donald Altschiller |editor5=Charles Walker Bassett |chapter=Who Does What?}}</ref>\n\n== Goals ==\n[[File:Jonathan Greenblatt by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|Jonathan Greenblatt, National Director and CEO of the Anti-Defamation League since 2015]]\nThe stated purpose of the ADL is to fight: {{quote|anti-Semitism and all forms of bigotry (in the United States) and abroad, combat international terrorism, probe the roots of hatred, advocate before the United States Congress, come to the aid of victims of bigotry, develop educational programs, and serve as a public resource for government, media, law enforcement, and the public, all towards the goal of countering and reducing hatred.}} Historically, ADL has opposed groups and individuals it considered to be anti-Semitic and/or racist, including: [[Nazism|Nazis]], the [[Ku Klux Klan]], [[Henry Ford]], Father [[Charles Coughlin]] (leader of the [[Christian Front (United States)|Christian Front]]), Nation of Islam leader [[Louis Farrakhan]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Antisemitism/ADL-pans-congressman-who-wont-condemn-Farrakhan-for-lacking-courage-544221|title=ADL pans congressman who won\u2019t condemn Farrakhan for lacking 'courage'|last=|first=|date=March 5, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> the [[Christian Identity]] movement, the [[German-American Bund]], [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazis]], the [[Militia (United States)|American militia]] movement and [[white power skinhead]]s (although ADL acknowledges that there are also non-racist [[skinhead]]s).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/racist_skinheads/ |title=Racist Skinhead Project |publisher=ADL}}</ref><ref>Salberg, Melvin. [https://www.nytimes.com/1994/04/29/opinion/l-adl-acknowledges-nonracist-skinheads-932108.html Letter to the editor (\"A.D.L. Acknowledges Nonracist Skinheads\")]. ''The New York Times''. April 29, 1994.</ref> ADL publishes reports on a variety of countries, regarding alleged incidents of anti-Jewish attacks and propaganda.  Along with the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC), ADL's Center on Extremism (COE) is generally viewed as the most authoritative non-governmental experts on domestic extremists in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/20/us/hate-groups-rise.html|title=Over 1,000 Hate Groups Are Now Active in United States, Civil Rights Group Says|last=Stack|first=Liam|date=February 20, 2019|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nADL maintains that some forms of [[anti-Zionism]] and [[criticism of Israel]] cross the line into anti-Semitism. The Anti-Defamation League states:\n{{quote|Criticism of particular Israeli actions or policies in and of itself does not constitute anti-Semitism. Certainly the sovereign State of Israel can be legitimately criticized just like any other country in the world. However, it is undeniable that there are those whose criticism of Israel or of \"Zionism\" is used to mask anti-Semitism.<ref>{{cite web|title=Response To Common Inaccuracy: Israel Critics are Anti-Semites|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/fact-sheets/response-to-common-inaccuracy-israel-critics-are-anti-semites|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 2010, ADL published a list of the \"ten leading organizations responsible for maligning Israel in the US\", which has included [[ANSWER]], the [[International Solidarity Movement]], and [[Jewish Voice for Peace]] for its call for [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|BDS]].<ref>Benhorin, Yitzhak. \"[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3969798,00.html Jewish group makes ADL blacklist].\" ynet news. October 15, 2010.</ref>  It has not published such a list since.\n\n=== Fighting antisemitism ===\nIn the second decade of the 21st century ADL and Jews, as well as non-Jews, throughout the United States were generally shocked at the global resurgence of antisemitism,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pope-antisemitism-idUSKBN1ZJ1LT|title=Pope condemns 'barbaric resurgence' of anti-Semitism|last=|first=|newspaper=Reuters|date=January 20, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> which was manifested in the rise of white supremacist extremist activity both online and off.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/17/695593556/-antisemitism-here-and-now-author-discusses-resurgence-of-public-anti-semitism|title='Antisemitism: Here And Now' Author Discusses Resurgence Of Public Anti-Semitism|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/anti-semitic-assaults-u-s-more-doubled-2018-adl-reports-n1000246|title=Anti-Semitic assaults in the U.S. more than doubled in 2018, ADL reports|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> A foundational theme of white supremacists was antisemitism, which accompanied or underlay the anti-Muslim, xenophobic, racist, homophobic and other bigotry of these individuals and groups.<ref name=\":3\" /> Social media in particular, amplified hatred and provided what ADL officials characterized as a virtual \"24/7 neo-Nazi rally.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishwebsite.com/featured/adl-urges-congress-to-help-social-media-giants-address-anti-semitism/50933/|title=ADL urges Congress to help social media giants address anti-Semitism|last=|first=|date=January 16, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The number of [[hate crime]]s and extremist murders shook the ADL, leading it to reformulate its strategy so it could devote more of its resources to fighting antisemitism and [[extremism]]: the [[Unite the Right rally|2017 white supremacist rally]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], during which extremists chanted \"Jews will not replace us\" and which led to the murder of [[Charlottesville car attack|Heather Heyer]]; [[Dylann Roof|Dylan Roof]]'s [[Charleston church shooting|2015 massacre of African Americans]] at a prayer group in [[Charleston, South Carolina]]; the murder of 11 Jews at Sabbath services in the 2018 [[Pittsburgh synagogue shooting]]; the 2019 [[Poway synagogue shooting]] in California; the 2019 [[Christchurch mosque shooting]]<nowiki/>s in New Zealand; the 2019 Monsey, NY [[Monsey Hanukkah stabbing|Hanukkah stabbing]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/30/opinion/monsey-new-york-attack.html|title=The Right Response to the Anti-Semitic Attack in Monsey, N.Y.|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 30, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020|last1=Lowey|first1=Nita|last2=Harris|first2=David}}</ref> the series of antisemitic hate crimes in Brooklyn, NY in December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/12/27/jewish-mom-son-assaulted-in-latest-anti-semitic-attack-in-brooklyn/|title=Four Jewish women targeted in latest anti-Semitic attacks in Brooklyn|last=|first=|date=December 27, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL has financially supported litigation against the organizers of the Charlottesville rally,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-announces-support-for-ifas-lawsuit-against-neo-nazis-white-supremacists-and|title=ADL Announces Support for IFA's Lawsuit Against Neo-Nazis, White Supremacists, and Hate Groups Responsible for Charlottesville Violence|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> lobbied for an array of federal and state laws and policies which are designed to track, expose, and combat extremism, and developed and marketed education programs about the subject.<ref name=\":4\" />  ADL also works in close collaboration with Law Enforcement in response to hate crimes.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/anti-semitism/anti-semitism-in-the-us|title=Anti-Semitism in the US|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, after a year's work, ADL published ''Antisemitism Uncovered: A Guide to Old Myths in a New Era.''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://antisemitism.adl.org/?_ga=2.171810404.555282254.1584044588-1012598960.1553545971|title=Antisemitism Uncovered: A Guide to Old Myths in a New Era|last=Anti-Defamation League|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The Guide is intended to be \"a comprehensive resource with historical context, fact-based descriptions of prevalent antisemitic myths, contemporary examples and calls-to-action for addressing this hate.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> It is organized around seven \"myths\" or antisemitic tropes, and composed of modules.<ref name=\":1\" /> This Guide also represented ADL's shift from using the spelling \"anti-Semitism\" to \"antisemitism.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://antisemitism.adl.org/?_ga=2.171810404.555282254.1584044588-1012598960.1553545971|title=Antisemitism Uncovered: Notes from the CEO, Footnote 8|last=|first=|date=|website=ADL|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/culture/166092/should-anti-semitism-be-hyphenated/|title=Should anti-semitism be hyphenated|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] also saw the launch of Jew hatred and at least two types of conspiracy theories that were resuscitated and revised so they could encompass the virus crisis,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/listen-tablets-yair-rosenberg-talks-anti-semitism-during-coronavirus-crisis/|title=Listen: Tablet's Yair Rosenberg talks anti-Semitism during coronavirus crisis|last=Rosenberg|first=Yair|date=March 27, 2020|website=The Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> an analysis with which ADL agreed and also exposed. \"'There are people out there in the conspiracy theorist swamp who are talking about this being some kind of Mossad thing, or Israel-operative thing,' Rosenberg said. And there's the other type of theorist 'who just celebrates when Jews die from it, under the cover that anti-Zionism makes it okay to celebrate when random people die.' Many of these people, he said, tweeted horrific things after Israel's first victim, Holocaust survivor Aryeh Stern, passed away.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=@JGreenblattADL|title=Tweet re@yair_rosenberg on #antisemitism and #coronavirusMarch|last=|first=|date=March 27, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Tracking extremists ===\nDuring the 1930s, ADL, along with the American Jewish Committee, coordinated American Jewish groups across the country in monitoring the activities of the German-American Bund and its pro-Nazis, nativist allies in the United States. In many instances, these community-based defense organizations paid informants to infiltrate these groups and report on what they discovered. The longest-lived and most effective of these American Jewish resistance organizations was the Los Angeles Jewish Community Committee (LAJCC), which was backed financially by the Jewish leaders of the motion picture industry. The day-to-day operations of the LAJCC were supervised by a Jewish attorney, [[Leon L. Lewis]]. Lewis was uniquely qualified to combat the rise of Nazism in Los Angeles, having served as the first national secretary of the Anti-Defamation League in Chicago from 1925\u20131931. From 1934\u20131941, the LAJCC maintained its undercover surveillance of the German-American Bund, the Silver Shirts and dozens of other pro-Nazi, nativist groups that operated in Los Angeles. Partnering with the American Legion in Los Angeles, the LAJCC channeled eyewitness accounts of sedition onto federal authorities. Working with the ADL, Leon Lewis and the LAJCC played a strategic role in counseling the McCormack-Dickstein Committee investigation of Nazi propaganda activities in the United States (1934) and the Dies Committee investigation of \"un-American activities\" (1938-1940). In their final reports to Congress, both Committees found that the sudden rise in political antisemitism in the United States during the decade was due, in part, to the German government's support of these domestic groups.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rosenzweig|first=Laura|url=https://nyupress.org/books/9781479855179/|title=Hollywood's Spies: The Undercover Surveillance of Nazis in Los Angeles|date=2017|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=9781479855179|location=New York|page=|author-link=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ross|first=Steven|url=https://www.bloomsbury.com/us/hitler-in-los-angeles-9781620405642/|title=Hitler in Los Angeles: How Jews Foiled Nazi Plots Against Hollywood and America|date=2017|publisher=Bloomsbury|isbn=9781620405642|location=New York|page=|author-link=}}</ref>\n\nSince the 1970s, ADL has partnered with the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) field offices, sharing information learned from monitoring of extremist groups.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=5SOAAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA167 \"Confronting Right Wing Extremism and Terrorism in the USA\"], George Michael. Routledge, Sep 2, 2003. p. 167. Retrieved 27 feb 2017</ref>  In April 2020, ADL joined with [[George Washington University's Program on Extremism]] to release a joint report on white supremacist terrorism, which supported additional government actions to combat the surging threat; the release of the report was timed to occur the same day that the U.S. government, for the first time, designated a white supremacist group and individuals associated with it a [[Special Designated Global Terrorist|Specially Designated Global Terrorist]] ([[Specially Designated Global Terrorist|SDGT]]) organization - akin to the [[United States Department of State list of Foreign Terrorist Organizations|Foreign Terrorist Organization]] (FTO) designation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.homelandsecuritynewswire.com/dr20200407-new-report-outlines-tactics-of-modern-whitesupremacist-terrorism|title=New Report Outlines Tactics of Modern White-Supremacist Terrorism|last=|first=|date=April 7, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hstoday.us/subject-matter-areas/counterterrorism/report-u-s-has-struggled-to-adapt-to-changing-domestic-terrorism-landscape/|title=Report: U.S. Has Struggled to Adapt to Changing Domestic Terrorism Landscape|last=|first=|date=April 7, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nADL keeps track of the activities of extremist groups and movements, primarily through its Center on Extremism.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/sites/default/files/documents/assets/pdf/combating-hate/ADL_CR_Bigots_on_Bikes_online.pdf|title=Bigots on Bikes: The Growing Links between White Supremacists and Biker Gangs|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-on-extremism|title=Center on Extremism|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> According to ADL Director Abe Foxman: \"Our mission is to monitor and expose those who are anti-Jewish, racist, anti-democratic, and violence-prone, and we monitor them primarily by reading publications and attending public meetings \u2026. Because extremist organizations are highly secretive, sometimes ADL can learn of their activities only by using undercover sources \u2026 [who] function in a manner directly analogous to investigative journalists. Some have performed great service to the American people\u2014for example, by uncovering the existence of right-wing extremist paramilitary training camps\u2014with no recognition and at considerable personal risk.\"<ref>\"A League of His Own\", letter to the editor, ''The Village Voice'' 38:20 (May 18, 1993)</ref> A person apprehended in connection to the [[2002 white supremacist terror plot]] had drawn a cartoon of himself blowing up the Boston offices of ADL.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/16/national/16PLOT.html|title=Boston Couple Plotted Blasts to Incite Race War, Prosecutor Says|date=July 16, 2002|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nADL regularly releases reports on [[Anti-Semitism in the USA|US anti-Semitism]] and extremist activities on both the [[Far-left politics|far left]] and the [[Far-right politics|far right]]. As part of its Law Enforcement Agency Resource Network (L.E.A.R.N.), ADL has published information about the [[Militia Movement]]<ref name=\"militia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/militia-movement|title=The Militia Movement|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en}}</ref> in America and a guide for law enforcement officials titled ''Officer Safety and Extremists''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/sites/default/files/documents/assets/pdf/combating-hate/Officer-Safety-and-Extremists-An-Overview.pdf|title=Officer Safety and Extremists|publisher=ADL|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref> An archive of \"[[Mark Pitcavage#Militia Watchdog|The Militia Watchdog]]\" research on U.S. right-wing extremism (including groups not specifically cited as anti-Semitic) from 1995 to 2000 is also available on ADL website.<ref name=\"militia\" />\n\nIn the 1990s, some details of ADL's monitoring activities became public knowledge; the ADL had gathered information about some non-extremist groups which became a contentious issue. In 2013, J.M. Berger, a former nonresident fellow of the [[Brookings Institution]], wrote that media organizations should be more cautious when citing the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC) and ADL, arguing that they are \"not objective purveyors of data\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Berger|first1=J. M.|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2013/03/12/the-hate-list/|title=The Hate List|work=Foreign Policy}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, ADL announced that they would be developing profiles on 36 [[alt-right]] and [[alt-lite]] leaders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/adl-releases-whos-who-guide-of-alt-right-and-alt-lite-extremists/|title=ADL releases 'Who's Who' guide of alt-right and alt-lite extremists|work=The Times of Israel|access-date=2017-07-19|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/from-alt-right-to-alt-lite-naming-the-hate|title=From Alt Right to Alt Lite: Naming the Hate|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref>  In 2019 and 2020 ADL executives and staff testified multiple times in front of Congressional committees concerning the dangers of domestic extremists,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/policy/defense-national-security/how-to-stop-it-congress-asks-what-the-military-is-doing-about-white-nationalism-in-the-ranks|title='How to stop it': Congress asks what the military is doing about white nationalism in its ranks|last=|first=|date=February 12, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> noting that the large majority of extremist murders in the United States over the past decade had been committed by white supremacists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/i-testified-at-a-congressional-hearing-on-white-nationalism-heres-some-of-what-i-wish-we-had|title=I Testified at a Congressional Hearing on White Nationalism. Here's Some of What I Wish We Had Discussed.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/adl-tells-congress-to-curb-online-hate-speech-if-social-media-giants-wont/|title=ADL tells Congress to curb online hate speech if social media giants won't|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> In early 2020, as the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Coronavirus pandemic]] raged, ADL's Center on Extremism<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-on-extremism|title=Who We Are: Center on Extremism|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> began tracking and publishing reports of upsurges in extremist hate and violence targeting Asian-Americans, Chinese, Jews and immigrants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/coronavirus-crisis-elevates-antisemitic-racist-tropes|title=Coronavirus Elevates Antisemitic Racist Tropes|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2020/03/20/yang-anti-defamation-league-ceo-avoid-coronavirus-scapegoating-racism-column/2877976001/|title=Yang & Anti-Defamation League CEO: Avoid coronavirus racism and scapegoating|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Separation of church and state   ===\nOne of ADL's major focuses is [[Freedom of religion#Judaism|religious freedom]] for people of all faiths.<ref name=\"RelFree\">{{cite web|title=Primer on the First Amendment & Religious Freedom|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/the-first-amendment-and-religious-freedom|website=Anti-Defamation League|accessdate=11 May 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Religious Freedom|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/discrimination/religious-freedom|website=Anti-Defamation League|accessdate=11 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> In the context of public schools, ADL has taken the position that because [[creationism]] and [[intelligent design]] are religious beliefs, and the government is prohibited from endorsing the beliefs of any particular religion, they should not be taught in [[science]] classrooms: \"The U.S. Constitution guarantees the rights of Americans to believe the religious theories of creation (as well as other theories), but it does not permit them to be taught in public school science classes.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adl.org/issue_religious_freedom/create/creationism_QA.asp |title=Religion in the Science Class? Why Creationism and Intelligent Design Don't Belong |publisher=ADL |access-date=March 6, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020407123320/http://www.adl.org/issue_religious_freedom/create/creationism_QA.asp |archive-date=April 7, 2002 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Similarly, ADL supports the legal precedent that it is [[constitutionality|unconstitutional]] for the government to post the [[Ten Commandments]] in courthouses, schools, and other public places: \"True religious liberty means freedom from having the government impose the religion of the majority on all citizens.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adl.org/10comm/Prohibitions.asp |title=The Ten Commandments Controversy: A First Amendment Perspective \u2013 Prohibitions on Display of the Ten Commandments |publisher=ADL |access-date=March 7, 2006 |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20020920090047/http://www.adl.org/10comm/prohibitions.asp |archive-date=September 20, 2002 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ADL has also condemned the public school [[Bible]] curriculum published by the [[National Council on Bible Curriculum in Public Schools]], saying that it raises \"serious constitutional problems\" and \"advocates the acceptance of one faith tradition's interpretation of the Bible over another\".<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Says Bible Teaching Guide for Public Schools 'Unacceptable' |publisher=ADL |date=November 7, 2005 |url=http://www.jewsonfirst.org/05a/public024.html |access-date=July 11, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022212940/http://www.jewsonfirst.org/05a/public024.html |archive-date=October 22, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 ADL opposed [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|Proposition 8]] in California; Prop 8 was a successful ballot proposition for a state constitutional amendment opposing same sex marriage that was subsequently overturned by the federal courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2008_California_Proposition_8|title=2008 California Proposition 8|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> ADL submitted amicus briefs supporting same sex marriage in those cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://38.106.4.56/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentID=1228|title=BRIEF OF AMICI CURIAE ANTI-DEFAMATION LEAGUE ET AL. IN SUPPORT OF RESPONDENTS|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307154233/http://38.106.4.56/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentID=1228|archive-date=March 7, 2013|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> While basing its ongoing opposition to that and other anti-LGBTQ+ laws and campaigns primarily on equality and anti-discrimination legal rationales, ADL also consistently cites church/state separation arguments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/its-not-ok-for-businesses-to-discriminate-in-the-name-of-religion|title=It's Not OK for Businesses to Discriminate in the Name of Religion|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Thus, a frequent theme of ADL argument is that freedom of religion was meant to be a shield to protect religious freedom (particularly of minorities and vulnerable constituencies), and not a sword to attack the religious freedom of others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/ADL-slams-controversial-religious-freedom-laws-in-US-396007|title=ADL slams controversial 'religious freedom' laws in US|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nADL has also based its support for women's equality and reproductive choice on, among other legal arguments, the argument that the state should not adopt as law a particular religious belief,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/abortion-bans-undermine-equality-for-all|title=Abortion and Religious Freedom: The Right-Wing Assault on Religious Diversity in Reproductive Freedom|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> although the United States federal courts have not accepted this religious freedom and state/church separation line of argument.\n\n=== Holocaust awareness ===\nADL holds the view that it is important to remember [[the Holocaust]], in order to prevent such an event from reoccurring. Along with sponsoring events opposing [[Holocaust denial|Holocaust deniers]] and revisionists, ADL has been active in urging action to end modern-day [[ethnic cleansing]] and [[genocide]] in places such as [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]], [[Darfur]], and [[Sudan]].{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} ADL gives out its [[Courage to Care Award]] to honor rescuers of Jews during the Holocaust.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}} ADL has also sharply criticized Holocaust Denial as antisemitism and particularly singled out Facebook for its refusal to remove Holocaust denial content from its platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2020/01/26/auschwitz-liberation-ban-holocaust-denial-on-facebook-column/4555483002/|title=Facebook should ban Holocaust denial to mark 75th anniversary of Auschwitz liberation|last=Greenblatt|first=Jonathan|date=January 26, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nADL spoke out against an advertising campaign by [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals]] (PETA) beginning in 2003 that equated meat-eating with the Holocaust. A press release from ADL stated that, \"PETA's effort to seek 'approval' for their 'Holocaust on Your Plate' campaign is outrageous, offensive and takes chutzpah to new heights. Rather than deepen our revulsion against what the Nazis did to the Jews, the project will undermine the struggle to understand the Holocaust and find ways to make sure such catastrophes never happen again.\"<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Denounces Peta for its \"Holocaust On Your Plate\" Campaign; Calls Appeal for Jewish Community Support 'The Height Of Chutzpah' |publisher=ADL |date=February 24, 2003 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/HolNa_52/4235_52.htm}}</ref> In May 2005, PETA apologized for its campaign, with PETA President [[Ingrid Newkirk]] stating that causing pain \"was never our intention, and we are deeply sorry\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Rabbinate to phase out 'shackle and hoist' animal slaughter. More humane method to be adopted following claims of cruelty|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=February 19, 2008|last=Wagner|first=Matthew|quote=PETA has denied being motivated by anti-Semitism and even mentions on its Web site the humaneness of traditional Jewish slaughtering methods when done properly. However, PETA has a history of controversial campaigns. On May 5, 2005, PETA issued an apology for its 'Holocaust on Your Plate' exhibit, which traveled to more than 100 cities. The exhibit compared the treatment of farm animals to that of victims of the Nazi concentration camps. PETA President Ingrid Newkirk said she realized that the campaign had caused pain: 'This was never our intention, and we are deeply sorry.'}}</ref>\n\nADL's Education Department focuses on Holocaust and Genocide Education, primarily through its Echoes and Reflections Program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://echoesandreflections.org/|title=CONFIDENTLY TEACH ABOUT THE HOLOCAUST |website=Echoes & Reflections|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Echoes and Reflections is sponsored by ADL, [[Yad Vashem]], and the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|United States Holocaust Museum]]. In 2019\u201320, ADL's national lobbying group and the regional offices refocused efforts on federal and state funding of Holocaust and genocide education, in part as a result of the upsurge of antisemitism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/why-we-need-legislation-to-ensure-the-holocaust-is-taught-in-schools|title=Why We Need Legislation to Ensure the Holocaust is Taught in Schools|last=|first=|date=February 21, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Federal and State Hate Crimes Legislation ===\nADL was also one of the lead organizations campaigning for thirteen years, ultimately successfully, for the [[Matthew Shepard Act|Matthew Shepard and James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Prevention Act.]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.duke.edu/news/michael-lieberman-81/|title=Michael Lieberman '81|last=|first=|date=|website=Duke Law News Releases|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/attorney-general-loretta-e-lynch-hosts-63rd-annual-attorney-general-awards-honoring|title=Attorney General Loretta E. Lynch Hosts the 63rd Annual Attorney General Awards Honoring Department Employees and Others For Their Service|last=|first=|date=October 21, 2015|website=|page=|type=U.S. Department of Justice News Release|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>  The hold-up in passing that law focused on the inclusion of the term \"sexual orientation\" as one of the bases that a crime could be deemed a hate crime.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/year-blaze-bernsteins-killing-parents-turn-alleged-hate/story?id=59754707|title=1 year after Blaze Bernstein's killing, parents look to turn alleged hate crime into 'movement of hope'|last=|first=|date=December 30, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> ADL also drafted the model hate crimes legislation in the 1980s; it serves a model for the legislation that a majority of states have adopted.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/hate-crime-laws-dont-prevent-violence-against-lgbt-people/|title=Hate Crime Laws Don't Prevent Violence Against LGBT People: So why do many LGBT people, and others, feel so deeply about the need to have them?|journal=The Nation|date=October 2, 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|last1=Bronski|first1=Michael|last2=Pellegrini|first2=Ann|last3=Amico|first3=Michael}}</ref>\n\n=== Online content moderation / fighting cyberhate ===\nAs part of its goal of opposing anti-Semitism, ADL has founded the \"Center for Technology and Society\" to target online harassment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-for-technology-and-society|title=Center for Technology and Society|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> The goal of this center is to combat cyberbullying through research, education, and active intervention via industry and law-enforcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-for-technology-and-society/about|title=About the Center for Technology and Society|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> The ADL has participated in [[YouTube]]'s Trusted Flagger program, and has encouraged YouTube to remove videos which they flag as hate speech, citing the need to \"fight against terrorist use of online resources and cyberhate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-applauds-google-and-youtube-in-expanding-initiative-to-fight-online-hate|title=ADL Applauds Google and YouTube in Expanding Initiative to Fight Online Hate|website=ADL.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2019/06/05/adl-praises-youtube-for-decision-to-remove-racist-extremist-content/|title=ADL Praises YouTube for Decision to Remove Racist, Extremist Content|website=Algemeiner}}</ref> CTS is also playing a lead role working with the online game industry to fight white supremacist activity on platforms connected with gaming.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/07/25/anti-defamation-league-65-of-gamers-have-experienced-severe-harassment-in-online-games/|title=Anti-Defamation League: 65% of gamers have suffered severe harassment online|last=|first=|date=July 26, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/two-thirds-of-us-online-gamers-have-experienced-severe-harassment-new-adl-study|title=Two-Thirds of U.S. Online Gamers Have Experienced Severe Harassment, New ADL Study Finds|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n\nADL supports [[Israel]] as a [[Jewish and democratic state]],<ref>[https://www.adl.org/resources/fact-sheets/response-to-common-inaccuracy-israel-cant-be-jewish-democratic Response To Common Inaccuracy: Israel Can't be Jewish & Democratic], Anti-Defamation League.</ref> and supports a [[two-state solution]] to the [[Israeli-Palestinian conflict]], negotiated by the parties.<ref>[https://www.adl.org/education/resources/fact-sheets/response-to-common-inaccuracy-bi-national-one-state-solution Response To Common Inaccuracy: Bi-National/One-State Solution], Anti-Defamation League.</ref> The organization vociferously opposed the [[UN General Assembly Resolution 3379|1975 United Nations resolution]] ([[UN General Assembly Resolution 4686|revoked in 1991]]) which equated [[Zionism]] with racism,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/durban/adl_quotes.asp |title=U.N. World Conference Against Racism |publisher=ADL}}</ref> and attempts to revive that formulation at the 2001 U.N. [[World Conference Against Racism]] in [[Durban]], [[South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/durban/un_anti-zionism.asp |title=U.N. World Conference Against Racism |publisher=ADL}}</ref> ADL also has expressed concern over Israeli legislative proposals that would stifle freedom of expression and undermine Israeli democracy.<ref>[http://www.adl.org/press-center/press-releases/israel-middle-east/adl-concerned-that-proposed-legislation-on-ngo-funding.html ADL 'Concerned That Proposed Legislation on NGO Funding in Israel Would Erode Nation's Democratic Character,'] Anti-Defamation League January 11, 2016:'In 2011, the League urged the Israeli government to work to modify two similar bills regarding donations from foreign governments to Israeli NGOs, and voiced concern over laws that stifle free expression.'</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/reform-joins-adl-ajc-in-opposing-israels-ngo-bill/|title=Reform joins ADL, AJC in opposing Israel's NGO bill|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nWhile ADL was a lead supporter of Congressional legislation prohibiting US individuals and businesses from joining \"unsanctioned boycotts\" such as the 1970s [[Arab League boycott of Israel|Arab League Boycott]] against Israel,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/glossary-terms/arab-economic-boycott|title=Arab Economic Boycott|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> it has taken a different, case-by-case approach to state anti-boycott laws more recently enacted in response to the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|BDS movement]]. Several of these laws, which seek to prohibit State agencies and instrumentalities from investing in companies that boycott Israel and from entering into contracts with entities that boycott Israel, have been successfully challenged in the courts. The legal challenges have primarily been brought by the [[American Civil Liberties Union|ACLU]] and [[Council on American\u2013Islamic Relations|CAIR]] on First Amendment constitutional grounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/26/us/texas-bds-law/index.html|title=Texas has a law that says contractors can't boycott Israel. But a federal judge just blocked it|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/blog/free-speech/arizona-lawmakers-running-scared-after-anti-boycott-law-ruled-unconstitutional|title=Arizona Lawmakers Running Scared After Anti-Boycott Law Ruled Unconstitutional|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL generally has not publicly supported laws it felt were constitutionally suspect under the First Amendment, both for legal reasons and because the organization believed that such laws, even if what ADL describes as \"well-intentioned,\" were not an effective means of combating the BDS movement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-urges-texas-city-to-remove-no-israel-boycott-requirement-from-aid|title=ADL Urges Texas City to Remove 'No Israel Boycott' Requirement from Aid Application|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> However, as a general matter the organization also has not publicly opposed such state laws, preferring to work behind the scenes to try to make such laws less infirm under the Constitution or to propose non-binding resolutions opposing BDS. A possible division of internal views in ADL was disclosed when the liberal Jewish news media organization, [[The Forward]], published ostensibly leaked internal ADL staff memos dating from 2016 that opposed the anti-boycott laws.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/news/416030/revealed-secret-adl-memo-slammed-anti-bds-laws-as-harmful-to-jews/|title=REVEALED: Secret ADL Memo Slammed Anti-BDS Laws As 'Harmful' To Jews|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL did not comment directly on the leaked memos, but the statement it issued in response appeared to acknowledge that there had been, if were not still, sharply divided views within the organization and that it did not try to suppress internal robust discussion.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nADL has publicly stated that it believes that certain founders and leaders of the BDS movement are antisemitic, but has noted that many supporters of BDS, both Jewish and non-Jewish, are not antisemitic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/backgrounders/bds-the-global-campaign-to-delegitimize-israel|title=BDS: The Global Campaign to Delegitimize Israel|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nADL has condemned the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]]'s (UNHRC)  list of companies doing business with Jewish settlements in Israeli-run territories (West Bank, East Jerusalem, Golan Heights), issued in February 2020, calling it a \"blacklist.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.com/news/world/310631/unhrc-releases-blacklist-of-companies-conducting-business-in-israeli-settlements/|title=UNHRC Releases 'Blacklist' of Companies Conducting Business in Israeli Settlements|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-strongly-condemns-un-councils-blacklist-of-israeli-companies|title=ADL Strongly Condemns U.N. Council's Blacklist of Israeli Companies|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, ADL condemned Senate Republicans in the United States for attempting to ban [[same-sex marriage]] with the [[Federal Marriage Amendment]], and called the proposal discriminatory.<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Welcomes Demise Of Same-Sex Marriage Amendment; Expresses 'Dismay' At Senate Vote |publisher=ADL |date=June 7, 2006 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/DiRaB_41/4832_41.htm}}</ref> That same year, the ADL warned that the debate over [[illegal immigration]] was drawing [[neo-nazis]] and [[anti-Semites]] into the ranks of the [[The Minuteman Project Inc.|Minutemen Project]].\n\nIn 2010, during a hearing for Florida House Bill 11 (Crimes Against Homeless Persons), which was to revise the list of offenses judged to be [[Hate crime laws in the United States|hate crimes]] in Florida by adding a person's homeless status,<ref>{{cite web\n| title = flhouse.gov HB 11 \u2013 Crimes Against Homeless Persons\n| url = http://flhouse.gov/Sections/Bills/billsdetail.aspx?BillId=42143&\n| accessdate = April 22, 2010\n}}</ref> the League lobbied against the bill, which subsequently passed in the House by a vote of 80 to 28 and was sent to the Senate,<ref>{{cite web\n| title = flhouse.gov HB 11 Apr 20 2010 \u2013 Voting record Florida House of Representatives\n| url = http://flhouse.gov/Sections/Bills/floorvote.aspx?VoteId=10836&BillId=42143&\n| accessdate = April 22, 2010\n}}</ref> taking the position that adding more categories to the list would dilute the effectiveness of the law, which already includes race, religion, sexual orientation, disability, and age.<ref>{{cite web\n| title = Homeless could be added to Florida's hate crimes law\n| url = http://www.miamiherald.com/2010/04/21/1589541/homeless-could-be-added-to-floridas.html\n| accessdate = April 22, 2010\n}} ''Miami Herald'', Miami Herald Media Co., April 21, 2010, by Lee Logan, Tallahassee Bureau: \"During a committee hearing on the bill, the Anti-Defamation League spoke against the bill, arguing that adding more categories to the hate crimes law would dilute its effect. But lawmakers were swayed by arguments in favor of protecting the homeless.\"</ref>\n\nWhen the [[anti-Mormon]] film ''[[The God Makers]]'' (1982) was produced, Rhonda M. Abrams, Central Pacific (San Francisco) Regional Director for ADL, wrote a critical review, including the following statement:\n\n{{quote|Had a similar movie been made with either Judaism or Catholicism as its target, it would be immediately denounced for the scurrilous piece that it is. I sincerely hope that people of all faiths will similarly repudiate ''The Godmakers'' as defamatory and untrue, and recognize it for what it truly represents - a challenge to the religious liberty of all.<ref>[http://www.fairmormon.org/perspectives/publications/the-truth-about-the-god-makers/ia Letter to Dr. Richard Lindsay], Director of Public Communications, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, May 25, 1984</ref>}}\n\nADL supports [[Comprehensive Immigration Reform Act of 2007|Comprehensive]] and [[DREAM Act]] legislation that would provide conditional permanent residency to certain illegal aliens of good moral character who graduate from U.S. high schools, arrived in the United States as minors, and lived in the country continuously for at least five years prior to the bill's enactment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Afirman que con el debate de reforma migratoria subieron los cr\u00edmenes de odio|publisher=EFE News Services|date=January 25, 2013|quote= La Liga Antidifamaci\u00f3n Jud\u00eda ( ADL ) asegur\u00f3 hoy que desde que se inici\u00f3 el debate sobre una reforma migratoria integral en Estados Unidos se ha registrado un aumento de los cr\u00edmenes de odio contra los hispanos. ... Por su parte, el director del Departamento de Asuntos Legales de ADL, Steven Freeman, dijo a Efe que esta organizaci\u00f3n aboga por una reforma migratoria integral y el Dream Act}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, ADL condemned remarks by [[Ovadia Yosef]] that the sole purpose of non-Jews was to serve the Jews.<ref>Mozgovaya, Natasha. \"[http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/adl-slams-shas-spiritual-leader-for-saying-non-jews-were-born-to-serve-jews-1.320235?localLinksEnabled=false ADL slams Shas spiritual leader for saying non-Jews 'were born to serve Jews'].\" Haaretz Service. October 20, 2010.</ref>\n\nADL has spoken out against [[McCarthyism]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Norwood|first1=Stephen Harlan|last2=Pollack|first2=Eunice G.|title=Encyclopedia of American Jewish History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IB3mBsgfIHQC&pg=PA245|year=2008|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-85109-638-1|page=245}}</ref>\n\nADL has supported some moves of the Trump Administration, and criticized others. For example, the organization welcomed President Trump moving the U.S. Embassy to Jerusalem, thereby underscoring that Jerusalem was the capitol of Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-welcomes-president-trumps-announcement-on-jerusalem-calls-for-focus-on|title=ADL Welcomes President Trump's Announcement on Jerusalem; Calls for Focus on Peace Negotiations and Reducing Tensions|last=|first=|date=December 6, 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> ADL CEO and National Director Jonathan Greenblatt traveled to Israel to join Trump administration officials at the official opening ceremony of the embassy in Jerusalem.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-celebrates-historic-milestone-as-us-embassy-opens-in-jerusalem|title=ADL Celebrates 'Historic Milestone' as U.S. Embassy Opens in Jerusalem|last=|first=|date=May 14, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> ADL has also called for key Trump Administration executive Stephen Miller, the architect of the Trump administration policies on immigration, to be fired and condemned him as a white supremacist.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Relations with religious and ethnic groups ==\n\n=== Relations with Arabs and Muslims ===\n{{See also|Projects working for peace among Israelis and Arabs}}\n\nIn 2012, ADL released a statement opposing groups like the [[Stop Islamization of America]] and [[Stop Islamization of Europe]], and activists such as [[Pamela Geller]] and [[David Yerushalmi]], describing them as \"anti-Muslim bigots\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/article/stop-islamization-of-america-sioa|title=Stop Islamization of America (SIOA)|website=Anti-Defamation League}}</ref>\n\nSince U.S. Reprentatives [[Rashida Tlaib]] (D-MI) and [[Ilhan Omar]] (D-MN) were elected to the U.S. House of Representatives in late 2018, becoming in 2019 the first two Muslim women to serve in the U.S. Congress,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5445303/ilhan-omar-rashida-tlaib-midterm/|title=Ilhan Omar and Rashida Tlaib Just Became the First Muslim Women Elected to Congress|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL at times has defended them from racist and [[Islamophobia|Islamaphobic]] attacks,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JGreenblattADL/status/1102207176746156035|title=Tweet from ADL CEO Jonathan Greenblatt|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> as well as from what ADL has viewed as partisan efforts to weaponize accusations of antisemitism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitchy.com/brettt-3136/2019/05/13/adl-ceo-says-its-unacceptable-for-elected-officials-to-weaponize-rashida-tlaibs-comments/|title=ADL CEO says it's unacceptable for elected officials to 'weaponize' Rashida Tlaib's comments|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Indeed, Rep. Omar's \"inspiring\" story, as the first Somali-American lawmaker, was included in a book commissioned by ADL. ''The Good Fight,'' published before Rep. Omar's election to Congress, tells the stories of Americans who have fought for equality''.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ADL/status/943186695666708481|title=ADL Tweet, December 19, 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegoodfightbook.org/|title=Publishers' blurbs for \"The Good Fight\"|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Since their election to Congress, however, ADL also has repeatedly and harshly criticized Reps. Omar and Tlaib<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-statement-concerning-rep-rashida-tlaibs-tweet-on-pending-bds-bill-in|title=ADL Statement Concerning Rep. Rashida Tlaib's Tweet on Pending BDS Bill in Congress|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-calls-on-house-leadership-to-take-action-after-rep-omars-anti-semitic|title=ADL Calls on House Leadership to Take Action After Rep. Omar's Anti-Semitic Tweets|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freebeacon.com/politics/adl-rejects-omars-good-faith-defense-asks-pelosi-to-condemn-anti-semitic-rhetoric/|title=ADL Rejects Omar's 'Good Faith' Defense, Asks Pelosi to Condemn Anti-Semitic Rhetoric|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> for what it deemed to be antisemitic remarks and the spreading of dangerous antisemitic tropes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/jan/28/rashida-tlaib-responds-after-adl-accuses-her-of-sp/|title=Rep. Rashida Tlaib responds after ADL accuses her of spreading anti-Semitic 'blood libel'|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Relations with African-Americans ===\nIn 1997, the National Center for Black-Jewish Relations of [[Dillard University]], a [[historically black college|historically black university]] in [[New Orleans]], awarded the director of ADL, Abraham H. Foxman, with its first Annual [[Martin Luther King, Jr]].\u2013Donald R. Mintz Freedom and Justice Award.\n\nIn 2004, ADL became the lead partner in the Peace and Diversity Academy, a new New York City public high school with predominantly black and Hispanic students. In celebration of [[Black History Month]], the ADL created and distributed lesson plans to middle and high school teachers about [[Shirley Chisholm]] (1924\u20132005), the first black woman elected to the [[US Congress]], and an important civil rights leader.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nADL has also publicly accused a number of prominent African Americans of being anti-Semitic:\n\n* ADL has catalogued a more than three-decade history of [[Nation of Islam]] leader [[Louis Farrakhan]]'s espousal of anti-Semitic rhetoric such as claims that certain Jews are \"not real Jews\" and that they are \"wicked deceivers of the American people\" who \"sucked [Americans'] blood\", and that powerful Jews promote homosexuality and control black leadership.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/special_reports/farrakhan_own_words2/farrakhan_own_words.asp |title=Farrakhan In His Own Words |publisher=ADL}}</ref> Farrakhan first attracted the attention of the ADL with comments in a March 11, 1984, radio broadcast saying that, \"[[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] was a very great man\".<ref name=\"finalcall\">{{cite journal |title=Farrakhan and the Jewish Rift; How It All Started |journal=[[The Final Call]] |url=http://www.finalcall.com/perspectives/rift.html}}</ref> Farrakhan insists that he was using the word 'great' in the sense of 'Great Depression' or 'great white shark'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.noi.org/judaism-religion/|title=Minister Farrakhan rebuts fraudulent \"Judaism is a Gutter Religion\" canard|date=August 5, 2010|publisher=}}</ref> and on June 24, 1984, he described the Jewish state as \"structured on injustice, thievery, lying and deceit and using the name of God to shield your dirty religion under His holy and righteous name.\"<ref name=\"finalcall\" /> ADL has urged various groups including the [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People|NAACP]] (whose leader [[Benjamin Chavis]] developed a working relationship with Farrakhan in 1994) to dissociate themselves from Farrakhan and his views.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Foxman |first=Abraham H. |authorlink=Abraham Foxman |date=July 20, 1994 |title=Today's N.A.A.C.P. Draws on History; Set Farrakhan Aside |journal=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9503E7DE143EF933A15754C0A962958260}}</ref>\n* In 1984 ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' reported that then-ADL national director Nathan Perlmutter said that Rev. [[Jesse Jackson]], Sr. was anti-Semitic, after Jackson referred to New York City as \"Hymietown\".<ref>{{cite journal |date=February 23, 1984 |title=Post Reaffirms Report On Jackson Comment |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=13 |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0E10FB3B5D0C708EDDAB0894DC484D81}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |date=February 27, 1984 |title=Jackson Admits Saying 'Hymie' And Apologizes At A Synagogue |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=16 |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F30A14F83C5D0C748EDDAB0894DC484D81}}</ref> However, ADL later reconciled with Jackson and has worked with him on the issue of the Iranian Jewish community.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Rev. Jesse Jackson Meets with Iranian Jewish Families Pledges to Intercede on Behalf of Imprisoned Jews |publisher=ADL |date=June 11, 1999 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/ASInt_13/3401_13.asp}}</ref>\n* Film Director [[Spike Lee]] was criticized by the Anti-Defamation League for his portrayal of Jewish nightclub owners Moe and Josh Flatbush in his film ''[[Mo' Better Blues]]'' (1990). The Anti-Defamation League said that the characterizations of the nightclub owners \"dredge up an age-old and highly dangerous form of anti-Semitic stereotyping\", and it was \"disappointed that Spike Lee \u2013 whose success is largely due to his efforts to break down racial stereotypes and prejudice \u2013 has employed the same kind of tactics that he supposedly deplores\".<ref>{{cite journal |date=August 16, 1990 |title=Spike Lee's Jews and the Passage From Benign Cliche Into Bigotry|journal=[[The New York Times]] |author=Caryn James|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/08/16/movies/critic-s-notebook-spike-lee-s-jews-passage-benign-cliche-into-bigotry.html}}</ref> Lee's portrayal also angered the B'nai B'rith and other such Jewish organizations, causing Lee to apologize via an Opinion-Editorial article in ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |date=August 13, 2006 |title=The Angriest Auteur|journal=[[New York Magazine]] |author=Ariel Levy|url=http://nymag.com/movies/profiles/19144/}}</ref>\n* During the 2002 election cycle, ADL, in a letter to ''The New York Times'', harshly criticized [[Congressional Black Caucus]] member [[Cynthia McKinney]] of Georgia for launching attacks perceived as racial against her Jewish opponent. According to an August 19, 2002, article in ''The New York Times'', ADL Director Abraham Foxman said, \"It made sense that Jewish Americans would want to contribute to efforts to replace Ms. McKinney\".\n* In February 2005, ADL National Director Abraham Foxman called it hypocritical for hip-hop producer [[Russell Simmons]] to lead an ad campaign against anti-Semitism while, in Foxman's view, also defending or excusing Louis Farrakhan's anti-Semitic statements.<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Calls on Russell Simmons to Distance Himself from Minister Farrakhan |publisher=ADL |date=February 14, 2005 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/ASUS_12/4645_12.htm}}</ref> Later that year ADL urged prominent black leaders including Simmons to reconsider their support for Farrakhan and [[Malik Zulu Shabazz]] organizing the [[Millions More Movement]] and to \"stand up\" against black anti-Semitism.<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Urges Prominent African-American Leaders to Reconsider Their Support for the \"Millions More Movement\" |publisher=ADL |date=May 2, 2005 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/ASUS_12/4707_12.htm}}</ref> Simmons, responding to ADL Director Abraham Foxman, said, \"simply put, you are misguided, arrogant, and very disrespectful of African Americans, and most importantly, your statements will unintentionally or intentionally lead to a negative impression of Jews in the minds of millions of African Americans\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.millionsmoremovement.com/news/russell-simmons05-09-2005.htm |title=Russell Simmons Responds to Abraham Foxman about the Millions More Movement |last=Simmons |first=Russell |authorlink=Russell Simmons |date=May 9, 2005 |publisher=[[Millions More Movement]]}}</ref> Foxman replied, \"If there were a Jewish event which was led by an out-and-out racist, I would expect Black leaders to say to me that ADL should have nothing to do with it. And I would agree with them, rather than condemn them for their action.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/media_watch/internet/20050510-Russell+Simmons.htm |title=Response to Russell Simmons |date=May 9, 2005 |publisher=ADL |access-date=March 16, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607153052/http://www.adl.org/media_watch/internet/20050510-Russell+Simmons.htm |archive-date=June 7, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Interfaith camp ===\nADL's New England Regional Office has also established a faith-based initiative called \"The Interfaith Youth Leadership Program\", better known as \"Camp If\", or Camp Interfaith. Involving teenagers of the Christian, Jewish, and Islamic faiths, the camp brings the teens together for a week at camp where the teens bond and learn about each other's cultures. The camp has emerged as a new attempt to foster good relations between younger members of the Abrahamic faiths.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Siek |first=Stephanie V. |date=April 6, 2006 |title=A different kind of camp |journal=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2006/04/06/a_different_kind_of_camp/}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n{{POV section|date=December 2018}}\n\n===Arab American and African American lawsuit against ADL===\nIn 1996, ADL settled a federal civil lawsuit filed by groups representing [[African Americans]] and [[Arab Americans]] that alleged that the ADL hired agents with police ties to gather information. ADL did not admit any wrongdoing, but agreed to a restraining injunction barring ADL from obtaining information from state employees who are forbidden by law to divulge such information. ADL also agreed to contribute $25,000 to a fund that funds inter-community relationship projects, and cover the plaintiffs' legal costs of $175,000.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1996-09-04/news/mn-40507_1_anti-defamation-league Anti-Defamation League Settles Lawsuit by Civil Rights Groups], LA Times, 4 September 1996</ref><ref>[https://www.jta.org/1996/09/06/archive/adl-to-pay-200000-to-settle-suit-alleging-spying-activities ADL to Pay $200,000 to Settle Suit Alleging Spying Activities], JTA, 6 September 1996</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QM1hloeMQqgC&pg=PA96&lpg=PA96&dq=%22Anti-Defamation+League%22+settlement+1996&source=bl&ots=d1L3G8qgX8&sig=Auo9IfPqSIcVRuL2g7zlDpFJTF4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjO5Y7Pr7XfAhWQDuwKHeNbB1MQ6AEwC3oECAIQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Anti-Defamation%20League%22%20settlement%201996&f=false American Jewish Year, Book 1998], page 96</ref>\n\n=== Armenian Genocide controversy ===\n{{Undue weight section|date=February 2019}}\nIn 2007, Abraham Foxman came under criticism for his stance on the [[Armenian Genocide]]. ADL had previously described it as a \"massacre\" and an \"atrocity,\" but not as a \"genocide.\"<ref name=\"http\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/Mise_00/5114_00.htm\n|title=ADL Statement on the Armenian Genocide\n|date=August 21, 2007}}</ref> Foxman had earlier opposed calls for the U.S. Government to recognise it as a \"genocide.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewcy.com/feature/2007-07-09/fire_foxman |title=Fire Foxman: Denying the Armenian Genocide should be the last atrocity perpetrated by the ADL chief.}}</ref> In early August 2007, complaints about the Anti-Defamation League's refusal to acknowledge the [[Armenian Genocide]] led to [[Watertown, Massachusetts]]'s, unanimous town council decision to end its participation in ADL's \"No Place for Hate\" campaign. (Watertown is known for its Armenian population.) In the subsequent months, some [[human rights]] commissions in other Massachusetts communities decided to follow Watertown's lead and withdraw from the ADL's No Place for Hate anti-discrimination program.<ref name=\"Woolhouse\">{{cite news|last=Woolhouse|first=Megan|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/12/05/adls_regional_leader_resigns/|title=ADL's regional leader resigns: Backers cite rift on genocide issue|date=December 5, 2007|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Esker/medford@cnc.com|first=Sharon Tosto|url=http://medford.wickedlocal.com/x96464381|title=City recognizes Armenian genocide, suspends ADL membership|work=Medford Transcript|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en}}</ref>  ADL had earlier received direct pressure from the Turkish Foreign ministry.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.co.il/hasite/spages/911393.html \u05d8\u05d5\u05e8\u05e7\u05d9\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc: \u05e2\u05d6\u05e8\u05d5 \u05dc\u05e0\u05d5 \u05dc\u05e2\u05e6\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d4\u05db\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d0\u05de\u05e8\u05d9\u05e7\u05d0\u05d9\u05ea \u05d1\u05e9\u05d5\u05d0\u05d4 \u05d4\u05d0\u05e8\u05de\u05e0\u05d9\u05ea] Haaretz, 10/10/07, Barak Ravid</ref> \n\nAlso in August 2007, an editorial in ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' criticized ADL by saying that, \"as an organization concerned about human rights, it ought to acknowledge the [[genocide]] against the Armenian people during [[World War I]], and criticize Turkish attempts to repress the memory of this historical reality.\"<ref>{{cite news |date= August 3, 2007 |url=http://www.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/editorials/articles/2007/08/03/a_genocide_not_to_be_denied/ |title=A genocide not to be denied |work=[[Boston Globe]]}}</ref> \n\nOn August 17, 2007, ADL fired its regional [[New England]] director, Andrew H. Tarsy, for breaking ranks with the main organization and for saying that ADL should recognize the genocide.<ref name=\"obrien\">{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/08/18/adl_local_leader_fired_on_armenian_issue/\n|title=ADL local leader fired on Armenian issue: Genocide question sparked bitter debate\n|work=The Boston Globe\n|first=Keith\n|last=O'Brien\n|date=August 18, 2007}}</ref> In an August 21, 2007, news release, ADL changed its position and acknowledged the genocide, but maintained its opposition to congressional resolutions aimed at recognizing it.<ref name=\"http\" /> Foxman wrote, \"the consequences of those actions,\" by the [[Ottoman Empire]] against Armenians, \"were indeed tantamount to genocide.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Brien|first=Keith|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/08/22/adl_chief_bows_to_critics/|title=ADL chief bows to critics: Foxman cites rift, calls Armenian deaths genocide|date=August 22, 2007|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The [[Turkish government]] condemned the league's statement.<ref>{{cite news|last=Levenson|first=Michael|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/08/24/turkey_condemns_statement_by_adl/|title=Turkey condemns statement by ADL|date=August 24, 2007|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> Tarsey subsequently won his job back,<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Brien|first=Keith|url=http://www.boston.com/news/globe/city_region/breaking_news/2007/08/antidefamation_1.html|title=Anti-Defamation League rehires New England director|date=September 7, 2007|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref>  but subsequently submitted his resignation, on December 4, 2007.<ref name=\"Woolhouse\" /> <ref>{{cite web\n |url          = http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/news/?content_id=4108\n |title        = Tarsy Resignation Draws Mixed Emotions From Area Colleagues\n |first        = Rachel\n |last         = Axelbank\n |publisher    = Jewish Advocate\n |date         = December 6, 2007\n |access-date  = January 7, 2008\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071210223450/http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/news/?content_id=4108\n |archive-date = December 10, 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nThe 2007 ADL \"Statement on the Armenian Genocide,\" was criticized by activists as failing to be a full, unequivocal acknowledgment of the [[Armenian genocide]], because the use of the qualifier \"tantamount\" was seen as inappropriate, and the use of the word \"consequences\" was seen as an attempt to circumvent the international legal definition of genocide by avoiding any language that would imply intent, a crucial aspect of the 1948 UN [[Genocide Convention]] definition.\n\nOn May 13, 2016, [[Jonathan Greenblatt]], then ADL's CEO and National Director for less than a year, published a blog post in which he wrote \"What happened to the Armenian people was unequivocally genocide\" and urged the U.S. to take a position recognizing the Armenian genocide.<ref>[[Jonathan Greenblatt|Greenblatt, Jonathan]] (May 13, 2016) [https://www.adl.org/blog/adl-on-the-armenian-genocide \"ADL on the Armenian Genocide\"] Anti-Defamation League website</ref>  In late 2019, ADL publicly endorsed and lobbied for a historic Congressional resolution commemorating the Armenian genocide, which passed the House of Representatives with bipartisan support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-endorses-congressional-resolution-commemorating-the-armenian-genocide|title=ADL Endorses Congressional Resolution Commemorating the Armenian Genocide|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/29/us/politics/armenian-genocide-resolution.html|title=House Passes Resolution Recognizing Armenian Genocide|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/12/us/politics/senate-armenian-genocide.html|title=Senate Passes Resolution Recognizing Armenian Genocide, in Defiance of Trump|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>  The U.S. Senate passed a similar resolution, which was also backed by ADL, but in December 2019 the Trump Administration, under pressure from Turkey's President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan|Recep Tayyip Erdogan]], refused to back recognition of the Armenian genocide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-armenian-genocide-erdogan-turkey-native-americans-a9250281.html|title=Trump refuses to back recognition of Armenian genocide after Erdogan threat|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Denver defamation suit ===\nIn 1994, ADL became embroiled in a dispute between neighbors in Denver, Colorado. Upon the involvement of ADL, the petty quarreling of next door neighbors, initially about garden plants and pets, quickly escalated into both civil and criminal court cases involving charges of anti-Semitism, and counter charges of defamation.\n\nCandace and Mitchell Aronson, Jewish next door neighbors of William and Dorothy Quigley, used a [[Radio Shack]] police scanner to listen in on the cordless telephone conversations of Mr. and Mrs. Quigley. When the Aronsons heard the Quigleys discuss a campaign to drive them from the neighborhood with \"Nazi scare tactics,\" the Aronsons contacted the Denver office of ADL. Upon the advice of ADL, the Aronsons then recorded the Quigley's private telephone conversations. The conversations included discussions of putting pictures of oven doors on the Aronsons' home (a reference to the Holocaust), burning one of the Aronson children, and wishing that the Aronsons had been killed in a suicide bombing. (The Quigleys later indicated that these remarks were not anti-Semitic, and were only intended to be sick humor.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/13674/edition_id/264/format/html/displaystory.html|title=Jewish News Weekly|publisher=}}</ref> Neither the Aronsons nor ADL were aware that Congress had amended federal wiretap law which made it illegal to record conversations from a cordless telephone, to transcribe the material, and to use the transcriptions for any purpose.\n\nNot knowing about the new federal law, the Aronsons used the tapes as the basis for a federal civil lawsuit against the Quigleys in December 1994. A day later, Saul Rosenthal, Regional Director of ADL, appeared at a news conference with the Aronsons in which he described their encounter with the Quigleys as \"a vicious anti-Semitic campaign,\" based solely on conversations he and associates had with the Aronsons. Later that day, Mr. Rosenthal expanded on his remarks in an interview on a Denver radio talk show.\n\nTwo days later, Jefferson County prosecutors used the tapes as the basis for filing criminal charges against the Quigleys.\n\nThe Quigleys became the target of scorn and ridicule. They received threats, and were forced to hire security guards for their home. A package of dog feces was mailed to their house. When they attended church, their priest openly chastised them in his sermon. The family was forced to shop in other towns, to avoid being recognized.<ref>{{cite web|title=Quigley v. Rosenthall|url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-10th-circuit/1360107.html|website=Findlaw|publisher=Findlaw|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref> Mr. Quigley's career with [[United Artists]] suffered serious damage.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lane|first1=George|title=Charges of bigotry backfire|url=http://extras.denverpost.com/news/news0429.htm|accessdate=June 23, 2015|issue=April 29, 2000|newspaper=Denver Post}}</ref>\n\nUpon investigation, and after assistant district attorney Steven Jensen heard on the tapes the context of Mrs. Quigley's remarks, all charges but one, a misdemeanor traffic violation against Mr. Quigley, were dropped. The district attorney issued two letters of apology to the Quigleys, saying he found no evidence that either had engaged in \"anti-Semitic conduct or harassment.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/05/13/us/privacy-rights-win-over-bias-charges-in-defamation-case.html | work=The New York Times | title=Privacy Rights Win Over Bias Charges In Defamation Case | date=May 13, 2000}}</ref>\n\nThe Quigleys brought a lawsuit against ADL, Rosenthal, the Aronsons, and two ADL volunteer attorneys. The two attorneys agreed to pay $350,000 to the Quigleys in settlement of their claims. The Quigley settlement with the Aronsons did not involve a cash payment. The Quigleys maintained their action against ADL and Rosenthal, which was heard in federal court. A federal jury returned a verdict of $10 million in favor of the Quigleys. ADL appealed.\n\nAccording to an April 13, 2001, article in ''[[The Forward]]'', upon hearing the appeal, a federal judge \"lambasted the ADL for labeling a nasty neighborhood feud as an anti-Semitic event\" and upheld most of Quigley's $10 million [[lawsuit]] for [[slander and libel|defamation]]. According to a report in the ''[[Rocky Mountain News]]'', with accrued interest, the judgment amounted to more than $12 million.<ref>{{cite news  |title=ADL Pays More Than $12 Million to Former Evergreen Couple |date=March 12, 2004 |newspaper=Rocky Mountain News |last=Abbott |first=Karen}}</ref>\n\n=== New antisemitism controversy ===\n{{Main|New antisemitism}}\nA book entitled ''The [[New Anti-Semitism]]'' (New York, 1974) by ADL national leaders Arnold Forster and Benjamin R. Epstein argued that a new kind of anti-Semitism is on the rise. A subsequent book, ''The Real Anti-Semitism in America'' (New York, 1982) was written by ADL national leader Nathan Perlmutter and his wife, Ruth Ann Perlmutter. In ''Never Again? The Threat of the New Anti-Semitism'' (San Francisco, 2003), by ADL's national director Abraham Foxman, he states on page 4: \"We currently face as great a threat to the safety and security of the Jewish people as the one we faced in the 1930s\u2014if not a greater one.\"<ref name=\"adl.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/Anti_semitism/never_again.asp |title=Never Again? The Threat of the New Anti-Semitism |publisher=ADL}}</ref>\n\nReviewing Forster and Epstein's work in a May 1974 issue of ''[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]'', Earl Raab, founding director of the Nathan Perlmutter Institute for Jewish Advocacy at [[Brandeis University]], argued that a \"new anti-Semitism\" was indeed emerging in America, in the form of opposition to the collective rights of the Jewish people, but he criticized Forster and Epstein for conflating it with anti-Israel bias.<ref>Raab, Earl. \"Is there a New Anti-Semitism?\", ''Commentary'', May 1974, pp. 53\u201354.</ref> Allan Brownfeld writes that Forster and Epstein's new definition of antisemitism trivialized the concept by turning it into \"a form of political blackmail\" and \"a weapon with which to silence any criticism of either Israel or U.S. policy in the Middle East,\"<ref>{{cite journal\n  |title = Anti-Semitism: Its Changing Meaning\n  |last = Brownfeld\n  |first = Allan\n  |journal = [[Journal of Palestine Studies]]\n  |publisher = [[Institute for Palestine Studies]]\n  |issn = 1533-8614\n  |volume = 16\n  |issue = 3\n  |year = 1987\n  |pages = 53\u201367\n  |doi = 10.2307/2536789\n  |jstor = 2536789\n  }}</ref> while Edward S. Shapiro, in ''A Time for Healing: American Jewry Since World War II'', has written that, \"Forster and Epstein implied that the new anti-Semitism was the inability of Gentiles to love Jews and Israel enough.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Shapiro|first=Edward S.|title=A Time for Healing: American Jewry Since World War II|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|year=1992|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780801843471/page/47 47]|isbn=0-8018-4347-2|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780801843471/page/47}}</ref>\n\n[[Norman Finkelstein]] has written that organizations such as the Anti-Defamation League have brought forward charges of new anti-Semitism at various intervals since the 1970s, \"not to fight antisemitism, but rather to exploit the historical suffering of Jews in order to immunize Israel against criticism.\"<ref name=Finkelstein21>{{cite book|last=Finkelstein|first=Norman|title=Beyond Chutzpah: On the Misuse of Anti-Semitism and the Abuse of History|publisher=University of California Press|year=2005|pages=21\u201322}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' has reported that the ADL has repeatedly accused Finkelstein of being a \"[[Holocaust denial|Holocaust denier]],\" and that \"these charges have proved baseless.\"<ref name=\"WP sparks\">{{cite journal |last=Powell |first=Michael |date=October 9, 2006 |title=In N.Y., Sparks Fly Over Israel Criticism |journal=[[The Washington Post]] |pages=A03 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/08/AR2006100800817.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Park51 Community Center controversy ===\nOn July 28, 2010, ADL issued a statement in which it expressed opposition to the [[Park51]] Community Center, a proposed Islamic community center and mosque near the [[World Trade Center site]] in New York. ADL stated, \"The controversy which has emerged regarding the building of a Community Center at this location is counterproductive to the healing process. Therefore, under these unique circumstances, we believe the City of New York would be better served if an alternative location could be found.\"<ref name=\"berk\" /> ADL denounced what it saw as bigoted attacks on the project. Foxman opined that some of those who oppose the mosque are \"bigots,\" and that the plan's proponents may have every right to build the mosque at that location. Nevertheless, he said that building the mosque at that site would unnecessarily cause more pain for families of some victims of 9/11.<ref name=\"berk\">Jacob Berkman, [http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2010/07/30/2740283/adl-opposes-world-trade-center-mosque ADL opposes World Trade Center Mosque] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100803005159/http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2010/07/30/2740283/adl-opposes-world-trade-center-mosque |date=August 3, 2010 }}, [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]], July 30, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jacoby |first=Susan |url=http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/spirited_atheist/2010/08/ground_zero_mosque_protected_by_first_amendment--but_its_still_salt_in_a_wound.html |title=The Spirited Atheist: Ground Zero mosque protected by First Amendment \u2013 but it's still salt in a wound|newspaper=The Washington Post |date=August 6, 2010 |accessdate=April 24, 2015| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100817115334/http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/spirited_atheist/2010/08/ground_zero_mosque_protected_by_first_amendment--but_its_still_salt_in_a_wound.html| archivedate= August 17, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes6\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/05/opinion/l05mosque.html | work=The New York Times | title=The ADL, the Mosque and the Fight Against Bigotry | date=August 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.adl.org/PresRele/CvlRt_32/5820_32.htm \"Statement On Islamic Community Center Near Ground Zero\"], Anti-Defamation League, July 28, 2010.</ref>\n\nThis opposition to the Community Center led to criticism of the statement from various parties, including one ADL board member, the [[American Jewish Committee]], the [[Jewish Community Relations Council|Jewish Community Relations Council of New York]], Rabbi [[Irwin Kula]], columnists [[Jeffrey Goldberg]] and [[Peter Beinart]], the [[Interfaith Alliance]],<ref>Adam Dickter, [http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/new_york/wake_adl_jewish_groups_back_ground_zero_mosque \"In Wake Of ADL, Jewish Groups Back Ground Zero Mosque\"], ''[[The Jewish Week]]'', August 3, 2010.</ref> and the [[Shalom Center]].<ref>Grace Rauh, [http://manhattan.ny1.com/content/top_stories/123265/jewish-leaders-rally-in-support-of-wtc-mosque/ \"Jewish Leaders Rally In Support Of WTC Mosque\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816033945/http://manhattan.ny1.com/content/top_stories/123265/jewish-leaders-rally-in-support-of-wtc-mosque |date=August 16, 2010 }}, ''[[NY1]]'', August 5, 2010.</ref> In an interview with ''[[The New York Times]]'' Abe Foxman published a statement in reaction to criticism.<ref>Abraham H. Foxman, [http://www.adl.org/ADL_Opinions/Interfaith/Mosque_Ground_Zero.htm \"The Mosque at Ground Zero\"], originally published in ''[[Huffington Post]]'', August 2, 2010.</ref> In protest of ADL's stance, [[CNN]] host [[Fareed Zakaria]] returned the Hubert H. Humphrey First Amendment Freedoms Prize ADL awarded him in 2005.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2010/US/08/07/new.york.zakaria.adl/ CNN host returns ADL award over stance on Islamic center], [[CNN]], August 9, 2010.</ref> ADL chair Robert G. Sugarman responded to a critical ''[[The New York Times]]'' editorial<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/04/opinion/04wed1.html A Monument to Tolerance], ''[[The New York Times]]'' editorial, August 3, 2010.</ref> writing, \"we have publicly taken on those who criticized the mosque in ways that reflected anti-Muslim bigotry or used the controversy for that purpose\" and stating that ADL has combated [[Islamophobia]].<ref>Robert G. Sugarman, [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/05/opinion/l05mosque.html \"Letter to New York Times\"] (August 4, 2010) ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU)\n*[[American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee]]\n*[[Antisemitism in the United States]]\n*[[Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations]]\n* ''[[Defamation (film)|Defamation]]'' (Documentary movie by [[Yoav Shamir]])\n*[[Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation]]\n*[[Israel lobby in the United States]]\n*[[Jewish Council for Public Affairs]]\n*[[Jews Against Anti-Christian Defamation]]\n*[[Membership discrimination in California social clubs]]\n*[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]\n*[[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.adl.org Official Website]\n\n{{Anti-Defamation League|state=expanded}}\n{{Antisemitism topics|state=collapsed}}\n{{Organized Jewish Life in the United States}}\n{{World Jewish Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Anti-Defamation League| ]]\n[[Category:1913 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Anti-racist organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish anti-racism]]\n[[Category:Jewish organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish political organizations]]\n[[Category:Opposition to antisemitism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1913]]\n[[Category:Political advocacy groups in the United States]]\n[[Category:Civil liberties advocacy groups in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Hersei", "label": "safe", "comment": "corrected punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-Defamation_League"}
{"title_page": "Masi Oka", "text_new": "{{Short description|Japanese American actor, digital effects programmer}}\n{{Japanese name|Oka}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Masi Oka\n| image       = Masi Oka by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| imagesize   =\n| caption     = Oka at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]\n| birthname   = Masayori Oka\n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1974}}\n| birth_place = [[Shibuya]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n|alma_mater   = [[Brown University]]\n| occupation  = Actor, occiasional rapper, producer, digital effects artist\n| yearsactive = 1998\u2013present\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Masayori \"Masi\" Oka'''|\u5ca1 \u653f\u5049|Oka Masayori|b. 1974}}<ref name= \"Biography Today\" /> is an American actor, occiasional rapper, producer, and [[visual effects|digital effects]] artist who became widely known for his role on [[NBC]]'s ''[[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]]'' as [[Hiro Nakamura]] and in CBS's ''[[Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|Hawaii Five-0]]'' as Doctor Max Bergman.<ref name=\"\u201cHeroes'\u201d Masi Oka is super-geeky\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/tv/heroes-masi-oka-is-super-geeky/|date=May 14, 2007|accessdate= May 4, 2018|title=\"\"Heroes'\" Masi Oka is super-geeky\"}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nOka was born in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]], to Setsuko Oka.<ref name= \"Biography Today\">{{cite journal |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |year=2007 |title=Masi Oka 1974- |journal=Biography Today |volume=17 |issue=1 |pages=99|publisher=Omnigraphics, Inc.|issn=1058-2347 |doi= |url= |accessdate= }}</ref> His parents divorced when he was one month old; he was raised in a single parent family and has never met his father.<ref name=\"tavis\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/kcet/tavissmiley/archive/200704/20070427_oka.html|title=Masi Oka|accessdate=2007-05-09|author=Tavis Smiley|date=2007-04-27|publisher=PBS}}</ref> He was six years old when his mother and he moved to Los Angeles from Japan.<ref>Biography Today, p.100</ref> At age eight, he appeared on the CBS-TV game show ''[[Child's Play (game show)|Child's Play]]''. In 1987, a 12-year-old Oka was featured as one of several children on the cover of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine, for the article \"Those Asian-American Whiz Kids.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Asian-American Whiz Kids |url=http://www.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,19870831,00.html |magazine=Time |date=1987-08-31 |accessdate=2008-12-17 |postscript=.}}</ref> Though he was not featured in the article itself, he was acquainted with the photographer who conducted the shoot.<ref name=\"Whiz\" /> In 1988, he placed fourth in the California state [[Mathcounts|MATHCOUNTS]] competition and was one of the four students to represent the state of California in the national competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elegantprofiles.com/blog/?p=4|title=Masi Oka (star of Heroes) on cover of Time in 1987|date=2006-11-21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207153917/http://www.elegantprofiles.com/blog/?p=4|archivedate=2009-02-07|accessdate=2008-11-11}}</ref> \n\nOka attended [[Brown University]], where he served as the musical director of [[The Bear Necessities]] all-male [[a cappella]] group.<ref>Rapkin, Mickey (2008). ''Pitch Perfect: The Quest for Collegiate A Cappella Glory'', p.11. Penguin Group, London. {{ISBN|1-59240-376-X}}, 9781592403769</ref> He graduated in 1997 with a [[Bachelor of Science|BS]] in computer science and mathematics and a [[Minor (degree)|minor]] in theater arts.<ref name=\"NYPost\" />\n\nOka landed his first job after graduation at [[Industrial Light & Magic]], [[George Lucas]]'s motion picture visual special effects company, with the hope of one day earning an [[Academy Award|Oscar]] for technical work on a motion picture.<ref name=\"NYPost\">{{cite news | last = Shen | first = Maxine | title = Heroes | newspaper = New York Post | date = 2006-10-15 | url = http://www.nypost.com/seven/10152006/tv/heroes_tv_maxine_shen.htm?page=0 | accessdate = 2007-03-12 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070224190904/http://www.nypost.com/seven/10152006/tv/heroes_tv_maxine_shen.htm?page=0 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-02-24}}</ref> Oka was also featured in the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' with ILM co-worker Anthony Shafer in a pre-dot-com article where he echoed his desire to meld acting and technology.<ref name=\"chron\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/e/a/1998/06/07/BUSINESS9847.dtl|title=Now Hiring|accessdate=|publisher=sfgate.com | first=George | last=Raine | date=1998-06-07}}</ref> He worked on the [[Star Wars prequel trilogy|''Star Wars'' prequel trilogy]].<ref name=\"Whiz\">{{cite web | url = http://www.tmz.com/2006/11/27/heroes-star-former-whiz-kid/ | title = \"Heroes\" Star: Former \"Whiz Kid\" | publisher = TMZ.com | date = 2006-11-27 | accessdate = 2007-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==Acting career==\n[[File:Masi Oka actor.jpg|thumbnail|left|Oka in 2007|alt=|250x250px]]\n\n=== 2000\u20132005: Move to Los Angeles and working actor ===\nOka first tried acting in 2000. He earned a [[Screen Actors Guild]] card by appearing in industry films, then moved to Los Angeles.<ref name=\"Wired\">{{cite magazine | last = Gaudiosi | first = John | title = Masi Oka: Coder, Actor, Hero | magazine = Wired | date = 2006-10-25 | url = https://www.wired.com/news/culture/0,71984-0.html | accessdate = 2007-03-12}}</ref> ILM stipulated in his contract that he could work at its Los Angeles branch but would have to return to their [[Marin County, California|Marin County]] location if he did not get cast for a recurring role that season. Oka later got cast on a pilot. Although the show was not picked up, it did satisfy the contract's requirements and he was allowed to stay in Los Angeles.\n\nDuring this period, Oka landed several minor roles in film and television, such as ''[[Austin Powers in Goldmember]]'' (2002) ''and'' the \"[[Dances with Couch]]\" episode of ''[[Yes, Dear]]''. {{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} He eventually got a recurring role as [[List of minor characters of Scrubs#Hospital staff|Franklyn]] on the NBC comedy ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]''.<ref name=\"Airborne\" /> \n\nHe was also featured in a North American commercial for [[Sega]]'s [[2002 in video gaming|2002]] [[PlayStation 2]] video game, ''[[Shinobi (PlayStation 2)|Shinobi]]'', with the catch phrase 'Shinobi's back!' in front of Sega's [[1987 in video gaming|1987]] ''[[Shinobi (arcade game)|Shinobi]]'' arcade cabinet.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n=== 2006\u20132010: ''Heroes'' and mainstream recognition ===\nIn 2006, Oka was cast as the time-manipulating [[Hiro Nakamura]] in the [[NBC]] television series ''[[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]]''. Oka translated his own dialogue for the show, from English to Japanese;<ref name=\"Living the dream\">{{cite news | last = Keveney | first = Bill | title = 'Heroes' star Masi Oka living the dream | newspaper = USA Today | date = 2006-11-09 | url = https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2006-11-19-hiro-main_x.htm | accessdate = 2007-03-12}}</ref> English subtitles accompanied his Japanese dialogue on the show. Prior to this, he was expecting to forgo acting by the end of that year's pilot season in lieu of pursuing writing and producing. ''Heroes'' turned out to be a breakout hit and his portrayal of Nakamura earned him nominations for both a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]] and a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]], the only actor on the show to be nominated on either award shows.<ref name=\"Airborne\">{{cite web|last=Kuhn |first=Sarah |title=Airborne at Last! |publisher=Back Stage |date=2007-02-09 |url=http://www.backstage.com/bso/news_reviews/features/feature_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003544143 |accessdate=2007-03-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927202759/http://www.backstage.com/bso/news_reviews/features/feature_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003544143 |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/heroes|title=Heroes|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> He was named the \"Coolest Geek\" at the [[Spike TV Guys' Choice Awards]] on June 13, 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7007610757|title=Spike TV Holds First Annual Guys Choice Awards Show|last=Casey|first=Jordan|date=June 11, 2007|website=All Headline News|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213183347/http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7007610757|archive-date=February 13, 2008|access-date=}}</ref> In 2007, he presented an award with ''Heroes'' co-star [[Hayden Panettiere]] on the 20th annual ''[[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards]]''.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn addition to his work on the show, he continued to work at ILM up to three days a week as a research and development technical director, writing programs that create special effects.<ref name=\"NYPost\" />\n\nHe played the role of Bruce in the big screen version of ''[[Get Smart (film)|Get Smart]]''. He played a [[real estate broker]] who is trying to sell to [[Seann William Scott]]'s character in Steve Conrad's ''[[The Promotion (film)|The Promotion]]''.\n\n=== 2010\u2013present: ''Hawaii Five-0'' and other projects ===\nOka plays the coroner [[List of Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series) characters#Dr. Max Bergman|Dr. Max Bergman]] in [[CBS]]' ''[[Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|Hawaii Five-0]]'', a remake of [[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|original series]] which aired from 1968 to 1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Masi-Oka--Hawaii-Five0-1021822.aspx|title=Heroes' Masi Oka to Play Hawaii Five-0 Coroner|publisher=TVGuide.com|accessdate=August 12, 2010}}</ref> He joined the show's main cast in the second series. His character was written as an ethnic Japanese who was adopted at birth by Jewish parents, hence his last name. Oka also made an appearance in the film ''[[Friends with Benefits (film)|Friends with Benefits]]''.\n\nIn 2015, Oka reprised his role as [[Hiro Nakamura]] in [[NBC]]'s ''[[Heroes Reborn (TV miniseries)|Heroes Reborn]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/masi-oka-as-hiro-returns-in-heroes-reborn/|title=Masi Oka returns as Hiro in 'Heroes Reborn'|publisher=cnet|date=March 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOka is fluent in [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[English language|English]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. He worked on the [[1992 Summer Olympics]] as an English, Spanish, and Japanese translator.<ref>Biography Today, p.101</ref> \n\nSimilar to his character Hiro Nakamura, Oka also collects [[manga]].<ref>SFX Collection - Special Edition #31: '''Total Anime''', page 15 (UK-based sci-fi magazine)</ref> He co-produced the [[Death Note (2017 film)|2017 American adaptation]] of the manga series ''[[Death Note]]''. He also founded the video game studio Mobius Digital Games, which is mainly known for its game ''[[Outer Wilds]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mobiusdigitalgames.com/team.html|title=Team - Mobius Digital|accessdate=2019-05-30}}</ref> \n\nHe carries the rank of [[Shodan (rank)|shodan]] in [[kendo]].<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Greg David|date=2007-01-18|title=There goes my Hiro|url=http://entertainment1.sympatico.msn.ca/There+goes+my+Hiro/TV_Guide/Interviews/Features/Articles/190107_masiheroes_greg.htm?isfa=1|magazine=TV Guide|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070216184327/http://entertainment1.sympatico.msn.ca/There%2Bgoes%2Bmy%2BHiro/TV_Guide/Interviews/Features/Articles/190107_masiheroes_greg.htm?isfa=1|archivedate=2007-02-16|accessdate=2007-05-10|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>Heroes Season 1 dvd, stunt special feature</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2001\n|''[[