{"title_page": "Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (2003 TV series, season 2)", "text_new": "{{Infobox television season\n| season_number        = \n| bgcolour             = #A22E36\n| image                = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| starring             = \n| country              = United States\n| num_episodes         = 26\n| network              = [[4Kids TV]]\n| first_aired          = November 8, 2003\n| last_aired           = October 2, 2004\n| prev_season          = [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (2003 TV series, season 1)|Season 1]]\n| next_season          = [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (2003 TV series, season 3)|Season 3]]\n| episode_list         = List of Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (2003 TV series) episodes\n}}\nThe second season of ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (2003 TV series)|Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]]'' originally aired between November 8, 2003 and October 2, 2004, beginning with the \"Turtles in Space, Part 1: The Fugitoid\" episode.<ref>[http://www.ninjaturtles.com/cartoon/newsynopses02.htm Season Two Episode list with detailed synopses at the Official Ninja Turtles website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080206004054/http://www.ninjaturtles.com/cartoon/newsynopses02.htm |date=2008-02-06 }}</ref> The episodes were first released on DVD in eight volumes, TMNT Volume nine through Volume fourteen. The volumes were released From May 18, 2004 through January 18, 2005. The episodes were later released in 2 part season sets; part 1 was released on February 19, 2008, containing the first 12 episodes of the season, and part 2 was released on October 28, 2008 with the final 14 episodes.<ref>[http://www.ninjaturtles.com/html/dvd_toons.htm TMNT DVD releases on Official Site] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070320044018/http://www.ninjaturtles.com/html/dvd_toons.htm |date=2007-03-20 }} ninjaturtles.com. retrieved on February 15, 2008</ref>\n\n==Story==\nPicking up from the first season's cliffhanger, the Turtles find themselves teleported to the alien world of D'Hoonibb, where they immediately are caught up in a war between the Triceraton Republic and the Galactic Federation. The two races are fighting over Professor Honeycutt, who has the plans for a teleportation device that both sides seek for their war efforts against each other. The Turtles end up on the Triceraton home world, and after saving Honeycutt, are teleported back to Earth by the Utroms. The aliens reveal themselves to be benevolent and reunite the Turtles with [[Splinter (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Splinter]], who they had healed after their last confrontation with the [[Shredder (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Shredder]], who survived the battle as well. His attack is foiled when the Utroms are able to teleport to their home planet with Honeycutt, and his true nature as an Utrom criminal named Ch'rell is revealed before he is defeated once again.\n\nIn the wake of the Shredder's defeat, a gang war erupts over control of his lost territory by the remainder of the [[Foot Clan]], the Purple Dragons (led by Hun), and the New York mafia (aided by [[Baxter Stockman]]). [[Leonardo (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Leonardo]] and [[Raphael (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Raphael]] argue over their place in fighting in the war, but the Turtles end up aiding [[Karai (character)|Karai]], the Shredder's adopted daughter, in claiming control of the New York Foot Clan and restoring order to the city. Though they part with a friendly ceasefire, the Shredder is revealed to have survived yet again, and Karai's loyalty to her father conflicting with her honor becomes a critical dilemma for her for the remainder of the series.\n\nIn the season finale, the Turtles follow Splinter to the Battle Nexus, a kingdom where a tournament is held between the multiverse's greatest warriors by the Ultimate Daimyo. The Turtles meet new allies in the form of [[Miyamoto Usagi]] and [[Murakami Gennosuke]], and end up working to defeat an attempted coup on the Daimyo's life by his own son and Drako, Splinter's old foe.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Michael Sinterniklaas]] as [[Leonardo (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Leo]]: the leader of the Turtles who seeks an alliance with Karai. (26 episodes)\n* [[Greg Abbey|Frank Frankson]] as [[Raphael (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Raph]]: Leo's second-in-command who often argues with him. (26 episodes)\n* [[Wayne Grayson]] as [[Michelangelo (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Mikey]]: the Turtles' youngest member and a large source of comic relief. (26 episodes)\n* [[Sam Riegel]] as [[Donatello (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Donnie]]: the Turtles' genius inventor. (26 episodes)\n\n====Supporting====\n* [[Darren Dunstan]] as [[Splinter (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Splinter]]: the Turtles' sensei and adopted father, the former pet of [[Hamato Yoshi]]. (18 episodes; ''(has no lines in episode 13)'')\n* [[Scott Rayow|Scottie Ray]] as [[Shredder (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Ch'rell/Oroku Saki/The Shredder]]: the main antagonist of the series and leader of the Foot Clan, whose true nature is revealed early into the season. (7 episodes)\n* [[Veronica Taylor]] as [[April O'Neil|April]]: a woman who develops feelings for [[Casey Jones (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Casey Jones]]. (9 episodes; ''(has no lines in episode 1)'')\n* [[Marc Thompson (voice actor)|Marc Thompson]] as Casey: an ally of the Turtles who develops mutual feelings for April O'Neil. (11 episodes; ''(has no lines in episode 1)'')\n* Scott Williams as [[Baxter Stockman]]: a brilliant, maniacal scientist who abandons the Foot for a majority of the season. (9 episodes)\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Greg Carey (voice actor)|Greg Carey]] as Hun: the Shredder's second-in-command, a hulking gangster and the leader of the Purple Dragons. Briefly broke away from the Foot to run the Purple Dragons full-time following the Shredder's disappearance, but later re-joined after the Shredder's return, though he lost his position as the Shredder's lieutenant to Karai.\n* Karen Neil as [[Karai (character)|Karai]]: the adopted daughter of the Shredder whose devoted service and loyalty to him conflicts with her sense of honor. After the Shredder returns, she becomes his new second-in-command.\n* Marc Thompson as\n** The Ultimate Daimyo: a warrior king who hosts a tournament of the multiverse's greatest warriors every 3 years.\n** Drako: a draconian warrior who carries a grudge towards Splinter for besting him in the Battle Nexus tournament years ago.\n* [[David Brimmer|Michael Alston Bailey]] as\n** Zanramon: the despotic Prime Leader of the Triceraton Republic.\n** Big Boss: the leader of the Mob.\n* [[Dan Green (voice actor)|Dan Green]] as\n** Mortu: the leader of the benevolent Utroms.\n** Commander Mozar: the second in command of the Triceraton Republic.\n* [[Jason Griffith]] as [[Miyamoto Usagi]]: an anthropomorphic rabbit samurai who the Turtles meet in the Battle Nexus tournament.\n* Frederick B. Owens as\n** Traximus: an honorable Triceraton gladiator the Turtles befriend.\n** [[Leatherhead (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Leatherhead]]: a mutant crocodile tricked into helping Baxter Stockman.\n* [[Ted Lewis (voice actor)|Ted Lewis]] as\n** Ue-Sama: a warrior prince who goes by the title \"Ultimate Ninja\", who seeks a battle with Leonardo.\n** Kluh: a hulking Levram warrior who becomes an enemy of Michelangelo.\n* [[Oliver Wyman (actor)|Oliver Wyman]] as\n** Professor Honeycutt/Fugitoid: a Federation scientist whose mind was accidentally uploaded into an android's body, who possesses the plans for a teleportation device warred over by the Triceratons and Federation.\n** General Blanque: the leader of the Federation.\n** Gyoji: the referee of the Battle Nexus.\n\n==Crew==\n''Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles'' was produced by [[Mirage Studios]], [[4Licensing Corporation|4 Kids Entertainment]], 4Kids Productions, and [[Dong Woo Animation]] and distributed by [[4Licensing Corporation|4 Kids Entertainment]] and was aired on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s Saturday morning kids' block in the US.<ref name=\"Dongwoo TMNT credits\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anidong.com/r2/en/co_production/ninja/sum.php |title=TMNT credits on Dongwoo Animation |publisher=Dongwoo Animation Co. |accessdate=2008-05-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219141426/http://www.anidong.com/r2/en/co_production/ninja/sum.php |archivedate=December 19, 2008 }}</ref> The producers were [[Gary Richardson (producer)|Gary Richardson]], Frederick U. Fierst, and Joellyn Marlow for the American team; Tae Ho Han was the producer for the Korean team.<ref name=\"Dongwoo TMNT credits\"/>\n\n==Episodes==\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Episode table|background=#A22E36 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=17 |director=11 |writer=37 |airdate=10 |prodcode=6 | episodes=  \n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=27\n |EpisodeNumber2=1\n |Title=Turtles in Space, Part 1 - The Fugitoid\n |DirectedBy=Chuck Patton\n |WrittenBy=Michael Ryan\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2003|11|8}}\n |ProdCode=S02E01\n |ShortSummary=The [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles|Turtles]] find themselves beamed halfway across the universe to the planet D'Hoonnib and right into the middle of a police action!\n\n* Villains: The Federation and the Triceratons\n* Based on Microseries, Fugitoid Issue #1, \"The Fugitoid\u2019s Origin\" and Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles, Volume One Issue #5, \"Teaming Up with Fugitoid\",Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles, Volume One Issue #5, \"Teaming Up with Fugitoid\" and Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles, Volume One Issue #6, \"The Triceraton Homeworld\".\n\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=28\n |EpisodeNumber2=2\n |Title=Turtles in Space, Part 2 - The Trouble with Triceratons\n |DirectedBy=Chuck Patton\n |WrittenBy=Michael Ryan\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2003|11|15}}\n |ProdCode=S02E02\n |ShortSummary=On the planet D'Hoonnib, the Turtles team up with the Fugitoid, a.k.a. Professor Honeycutt, a scientist trapped